nodes.description: Any constituent part of the host cell cytoplasm, all of the contents of a cell excluding the plasma membrane and nucleus, but including other subcellular structures. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: symbiont-containing vacuole
nodes.description: Membrane-bounded vacuole within a host cell in which a symbiont organism resides. The vacuole membrane is derived from both the host and symbiont.

nodes.name: infected host cell surface knob
nodes.description: Protrusion that develops in the plasma membrane of a parasitized erythrocyte. An example of this component is found in Plasmodium species.

nodes.name: Maurer's cleft
nodes.description: A disk-like structure that appears at the periphery of a red blood cell infected by an apicomplexan parasite, characterized by a translucent lumen and an electron-dense coat of variable thickness; often appears to be tethered to the host cell membrane by fibrous connections with the erythrocyte cytoskeleton.

nodes.name: host cell mitochondrion
nodes.description: A semiautonomous, self replicating organelle as found in host cells that occurs in varying numbers, shapes, and sizes in the cell cytoplasm. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: cytoplasmic viral factory
nodes.description: A viral factory located in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

nodes.name: viroplasm viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory that is electron dense due to high levels of viral RNA. Produced by nucleo-cytoplasmic large DNA viruses (NCLDV) like Poxviridae, Asfarviridae and Iridoviridae, and dsRNA viruses like Reoviridae.

nodes.name: spherule viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory which is a 50-400nm diameter membrane invagination. Spherules can appear on several enveloped cellular components depending on the virus.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory that consists of a double-membrane bound vesicle. Has a diameter of 200-300nm and is derived from the endoplasmic reticulum or Golgi apparatus. Produced by Picornaviridae, Nidovirales, Arteriviridae and Coronaviridae.

nodes.name: tube viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory derived from the Golgi in which Bunyaviridae replication takes place. Tubes are membranous structures close to the assembly and budding sites, and their function may be to connect viral replication and morphogenesis inside viral factories.

nodes.name: host cell viral assembly compartment
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded compartment that forms in the cytoplasm of the host cell, in which virus assembly takes place.

nodes.name: host symbiosome
nodes.description: A double-enveloped cell compartment, composed of the endosymbiont with its plasmalemma (as inner envelope) and an outer envelope (the perisymbiontic membrane) derived from the host cell.

nodes.name: host bacteroid-containing symbiosome
nodes.description: A symbiosome containing any of various structurally modified bacteria, such as those occurring on the root nodules of leguminous plants, of a host cell.

nodes.name: host thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The pigmented membrane of any host thylakoid.

nodes.name: host cell chloroplast thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: Any sac-like membranous structures (cisternae) in a chloroplast found in host cells, combined into stacks (grana) and present singly in the stroma (stroma thylakoids or frets) as interconnections between grana. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: host cell cytoplasmic vesicle
nodes.description: A vesicle formed of membrane or protein, found in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

nodes.name: host cell synaptic vesicle
nodes.description: A secretory organelle of a host cell, some 50 nm in diameter, of presynaptic nerve terminals; accumulates in high concentrations of neurotransmitters and secretes these into the synaptic cleft by fusion with the 'active zone' of the presynaptic plasma membrane.

nodes.name: host cell cytoplasmic vesicle membrane
nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell cytoplasmic vesicle.

nodes.name: host cell endocytic vesicle membrane
nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a host cell endocytic vesicle.

nodes.name: host cell synaptic vesicle membrane
nodes.description: The lipid bilayer surrounding a host synaptic vesicle.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory membrane
nodes.description: One of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory inner membrane
nodes.description: The inner of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory outer membrane
nodes.description: The outer of the two endoplasmic reticulum-derived lipid bilayer membranes that bound a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

nodes.name: host cell cytosol
nodes.description: The part of the host cell cytoplasm that does not contain organelles but which does contain other particulate matter, such as protein complexes.

nodes.name: host cell endoplasmic reticulum
nodes.description: The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host ER takes two forms, rough (or granular), with ribosomes adhering to the outer surface, and smooth (with no ribosomes attached).

nodes.name: host cell rough endoplasmic reticulum
nodes.description: The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host rough ER has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface.

nodes.name: host cell smooth endoplasmic reticulum
nodes.description: The irregular network of unit membranes, visible only by electron microscopy, that occurs in the host cell cytoplasm of many eukaryotic cells. The membranes form a complex meshwork of tubular channels, which are often expanded into slitlike cavities called cisternae. The host smooth ER has no ribosomes adhering to the outer surface.

nodes.name: host cell endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the host cell endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: host cell endoplasmic reticulum-Golgi intermediate compartment
nodes.description: A complex system of membrane-bounded compartments located between host cell endoplasmic reticulum (ER) and the host Golgi complex, with a distinctive membrane protein composition; involved in ER-to-Golgi transport.

nodes.name: host cell endosome
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded organelle that carries materials newly ingested by endocytosis. It passes many of the materials to host cell lysosomes for degradation.

nodes.name: host cell late endosome
nodes.description: A prelysosomal endocytic organelle differentiated from host early endosomes by lower lumenal pH and different protein composition. Host late endosomes are more spherical than early endosomes and are mostly juxtanuclear, being concentrated near the microtubule organizing center.

nodes.name: host multivesicular body
nodes.description: A late endosome in which regions of the limiting host cell endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; host membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the host cytoplasm.

nodes.name: host cell Golgi apparatus
nodes.description: A compound membranous cytoplasmic organelle of eukaryotic host cells, consisting of flattened, ribosome-free vesicles arranged in a more or less regular stack.

nodes.name: host cell lipid droplet
nodes.description: Any particle of coalesced lipids in the cytoplasm of a host cell. May include associated proteins.

nodes.name: host cell lysosome
nodes.description: A small lytic vacuole that has cell cycle-independent morphology and is found in most host animal cells and that contains a variety of hydrolases, most of which have their maximal activities in the pH range 5-6. The contained enzymes display latency if properly isolated. About 40 different lysosomal hydrolases are known and host cell lysosomes have a great variety of morphologies and functions.

nodes.name: host cell mitochondrial envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the host cell mitochondrion and separating its contents from the host cell cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: host cell perinuclear region of cytoplasm
nodes.description: The host cell cytoplasm situated near, or occurring around, the host nucleus.

nodes.name: host cell mitochondrial intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the host cell mitochondrial envelope.

nodes.name: host cell endosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the host cell endosome.

nodes.name: tubovesicular membrane network
nodes.description: A complex, symbiont-induced host-derived organelle that is comprised of multiple protein and lipid domains.

nodes.name: host cell peroxisome
nodes.description: A small host cell organelle enclosed by a single membrane, and found in most eukaryotic cells. Contains peroxidases and other enzymes involved in a variety of metabolic processes including free radical detoxification, lipid catabolism and biosynthesis, and hydrogen peroxide metabolism.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory lumen
nodes.description: The volume surrounded by the inner membrane of a double membrane vesicle viral factory.

nodes.name: host cell viral nucleoid
nodes.description: The region of a host cell that contains the viral genome.

nodes.name: host cell nuclear part
nodes.description: Any constituent part of a host cell's nucleus, a membrane-bounded organelle of eukaryotic cells in which chromosomes are housed and replicated. The host is the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: viral replication complex
nodes.description: Specific locations and structures in the virus infected cell involved in replicating the viral genome.

nodes.name: host cell nucleoplasm
nodes.description: That part of a host cell's nuclear content other than the chromosomes or the nucleolus. The host is the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: host cell nucleolus
nodes.description: A small, dense body one or more of which are present in the nucleus of eukaryotic host cells.

nodes.name: host cell nuclear envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the host nucleus and separating its contents from the rest of the host cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space, a gap of width 20-40 nm (also called the perinuclear space).

nodes.name: host cell nuclear lamina
nodes.description: The fibrous, electron-dense layer lying on the nucleoplasmic side of the inner membrane of a host cell nucleus, composed of lamin filaments.

nodes.name: host cell nuclear matrix
nodes.description: The dense fibrillar network lying on the inner side of the host nuclear membrane.

nodes.name: host cell Cajal body
nodes.description: A class of nuclear body in the eukaryotic host cell, first seen after silver staining by Ramon y Cajal in 1903, enriched in small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, and certain general RNA polymerase II transcription factors; ultrastructurally, they appear as a tangle of coiled, electron-dense threads roughly 0.5 micrometers in diameter; involved in aspects of snRNP biogenesis; the protein coilin serves as a marker for Cajal bodies. Some argue that Cajal bodies are the sites for preassembly of transcriptosomes, unitary particles involved in transcription and processing of RNA. The host is the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: host cell PML body
nodes.description: A nuclear body that reacts against SP100 auto-antibodies (PML = promyelocytic leukemia) located within a cell of a host organism.

nodes.name: host cell postsynaptic membrane
nodes.description: A postsynaptic membrane that is part of a host cell. A postsynaptic membrane is a specialized area of membrane facing the presynaptic membrane on the tip of the nerve ending and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft). Neurotransmitters transmit the signal across the synaptic cleft to the postsynaptic membrane.

nodes.name: viral factory
nodes.description: An intracellular compartment in a host cell which increases the efficiency of viral replication, and shields the virus from host defenses. Viral factories can be either cytoplasmic or nuclear and often arise from extensive rearrangement of host cell cytoskeletal and/or cell membrane compartments.

nodes.name: cytoplasmic viral factory
nodes.description: A viral factory located in the cytoplasm of a host cell.

nodes.name: viroplasm viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory that is electron dense due to high levels of viral RNA. Produced by nucleo-cytoplasmic large DNA viruses (NCLDV) like Poxviridae, Asfarviridae and Iridoviridae, and dsRNA viruses like Reoviridae.

nodes.name: spherule viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory which is a 50-400nm diameter membrane invagination. Spherules can appear on several enveloped cellular components depending on the virus.

nodes.name: double membrane vesicle viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory that consists of a double-membrane bound vesicle. Has a diameter of 200-300nm and is derived from the endoplasmic reticulum or Golgi apparatus. Produced by Picornaviridae, Nidovirales, Arteriviridae and Coronaviridae.

nodes.name: tube viral factory
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic viral factory derived from the Golgi in which Bunyaviridae replication takes place. Tubes are membranous structures close to the assembly and budding sites, and their function may be to connect viral replication and morphogenesis inside viral factories.

nodes.name: host cell viral assembly compartment
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded compartment that forms in the cytoplasm of the host cell, in which virus assembly takes place.

nodes.name: nuclear viral factory
nodes.description: A viral factory located in the nucleus of a host cell.

nodes.name: virogenic stroma
nodes.description: A nuclear viral factory formed by Baculoviruses. A vesicular structure in which virions are assembled.

nodes.name: peristromal region viral factory
nodes.description: A nuclear viral factory formed at the periphery of the host cell nucleus by Baculoviruses.

nodes.name: replication compartment
nodes.description: Globular nuclear domains where the transcription and replication of the viral genome occurs. More than one site can be present simultaneously.

nodes.name: host intracellular region
nodes.description: That space within the plasma membrane of a host cell.

nodes.name: host peribacteroid membrane
nodes.description: A host-derived membrane that surrounds one or more bacteroids (such as nitrogen-fixing bacteroids within legume root nodule cells).

nodes.name: host peribacteroid fluid
nodes.description: The soluble material inside the peribacteroid membrane, but outside of the bacteroid, within a bacteroid-containing symbiosome of a host cell.

nodes.name: host cell membrane pore complex
nodes.description: Any small opening in a host cell membrane that allows the passage of gases and/or liquids, composed of host proteins.

nodes.name: host caveola
nodes.description: A small pit, depression, or invagination, such as any of the minute pits or incuppings of the host cell membrane formed during pinocytosis, that communicates with the outside of a host cell and extends inward, indenting the host cytoplasm and the host cell membrane. Such caveolae may be pinched off to form free vesicles within the host cytoplasm. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: host cell junction
nodes.description: A plasma membrane part that forms a specialized region of connection between two host cells or between a host cell and the host extracellular matrix. At a host cell junction, anchoring proteins extend through the host plasma membrane to link cytoskeletal proteins in one cell to cytoskeletal proteins in neighboring cells or to proteins in the extracellular matrix.

nodes.name: host cell plasmodesma
nodes.description: A fine cytoplasmic channel, found in all higher plants, that connects the cytoplasm of one host cell to that of an adjacent host cell.

nodes.name: host cell projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a host cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.

nodes.name: host cell filopodium
nodes.description: Thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile host cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal growth cone; usually approximately 0.1 um wide, 5-10 um long, can be up to 50 um long in axon growth cones; contains a loose bundle of about 20 actin filaments oriented with their plus ends pointing outward.

nodes.name: host cell uropod
nodes.description: A host cell membrane projection with related cytoskeletal components at the trailing edge of a cell in the process of migrating or being activated, found on the opposite side of the cell from the leading edge or immunological synapse, respectively.

nodes.name: host cell wall
nodes.description: The rigid or semi-rigid envelope lying outside the host cell membrane of plant, fungal, and most prokaryotic cells, maintaining their shape and protecting them from osmotic lysis. In plants it is made of cellulose and, often, lignin; in fungi it is composed largely of polysaccharides; in bacteria it is composed of peptidoglycan.

nodes.name: host cell synapse
nodes.description: The junction between a nerve fiber of one host neuron and another host neuron or muscle fiber or glial cell; the site of interneuronal communication.

nodes.name: host cell surface
nodes.description: The external part of the host cell wall and/or host plasma membrane.

nodes.name: host cell periplasmic space
nodes.description: The region between the inner (cytoplasmic) and outer host membrane (Gram-negative Bacteria) or inner host membrane and host cell wall (Fungi).

nodes.name: host cell envelope
nodes.description: An envelope that surrounds a bacterial host cell and includes the host cytoplasmic membrane and everything external, encompassing the host periplasmic space, host cell wall, and host outer membrane if present.

nodes.name: host cell presynaptic membrane
nodes.description: A specialized area of membrane of the host axon terminal that faces the plasma membrane of the host neuron or muscle fiber with which the axon terminal establishes a synaptic junction; many host synaptic junctions exhibit structural presynaptic characteristics, such as conical, electron-dense internal protrusions, that distinguish it from the remainder of the axon plasma membrane.

nodes.name: host cell periphery
nodes.description: The part of a cell encompassing the cell cortex, the plasma membrane, and any external encapsulating structures of a host cell.

nodes.name: pathogen-containing vacuole
nodes.description: A membrane-bound intracellular compartment that is formed upon internalization of a pathogen into a host cell, and in which the pathogen resides.

nodes.name: viral occlusion body
nodes.description: A crystalline protein matrix surrounding the nucleocapsids of some insect viruses after their release in the environment. Produced in the host cell, the occlusion body protects the infectious virion after death of the host.

nodes.name: host apoplast
nodes.description: The apoplast region surrounding a host plant cell. Plants may be described as having two major compartments: the living symplast and the non-living apoplast. The apoplast is external to the plasma membrane and includes cell walls, intercellular spaces and the lumen of dead structures such as xylem vessels. Water and solutes pass freely through it. The host is defined as the larger of the organisms involved in a symbiotic interaction.

nodes.name: host extracellular space
nodes.description: The space within a host but external to the plasma membrane of host cells, e.g. within host bloodstream.

nodes.name: host cell
nodes.description: A cell within a host organism. Includes the host plasma membrane and any external encapsulating structures such as the host cell wall and cell envelope.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of membrane
nodes.description: The component of a membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of plasma membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plasma membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of external side of plasma membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plasma membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its external surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of periplasmic side of plasma membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plasma membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its periplasmic surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of cytoplasmic side of plasma membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plasma membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its cytoplasmic surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of synaptic membrane
nodes.description: The component of the synaptic membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of presynaptic membrane
nodes.description: The component of the presynaptic membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of presynaptic active zone membrane
nodes.description: The component of the presynaptic active zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of presynaptic endocytic zone membrane
nodes.description: The component of the presynaptic endocytic zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic specialization membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic specialization membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic density membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic density membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic endocytic zone
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic endocytic zone membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of cell outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of the cell outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of external side of cell outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of a cell outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its external surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of external side of mycolate outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of mycolate membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its external surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of periplasmic side of cell outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of the cell outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to periplasmic surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of mycolate outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of mycolate outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of external side of mycolate outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of mycolate membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its external surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of organelle membrane
nodes.description: The component of an organelle membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of intraperoxisomal membrane
nodes.description: The component of the intraperoxisomal membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of endosome membrane
nodes.description: The component of an endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic endosome membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic early endosome membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic early endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of postsynaptic recycling endosome membrane
nodes.description: The component of the postsynaptic recycling endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of presynaptic endosome membrane
nodes.description: The component of the presynaptic endosome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of mitochondrial inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of mitochondrial inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of matrix side of mitochondrial inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of the matrix side of the mitochondrial inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of mitochondrial outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of a mitochondrial outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of nuclear outer membrane
nodes.description: The component of a nuclear outer membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of plastid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of lumenal side of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its lumenal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of stromal side of plastid inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its stromal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of stromal side of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its stromal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of plastid inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of lumenal side of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its lumenal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of stromal side of plastid inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its stromal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of endoplasmic reticulum membrane
nodes.description: The component of the endoplasmic reticulum membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of Golgi membrane
nodes.description: The component of a Golgi membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of omegasome membrane
nodes.description: The component of the omegasome membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of phagophore assembly site membrane
nodes.description: The component of the phagophore assembly site membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of synaptic vesicle membrane
nodes.description: The component of the synaptic vesicle membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of dense core granule membrane
nodes.description: The component of the dense core granule membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of neuronal dense core vesicle membrane
nodes.description: The component of the neuronal dense core vesicle membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to one of its surfaces, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of lumenal side of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its lumenal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of stromal side of plastid inner membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid inner membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its stromal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: extrinsic component of stromal side of plastid thylakoid membrane
nodes.description: The component of a plastid thylakoid membrane consisting of gene products and protein complexes that are loosely bound to its stromal surface, but not integrated into the hydrophobic region.

nodes.name: apical complex
nodes.description: A group of cytoskeletal structures and associated membrane-bounded organelles found at the anterior end of adult obligate intracellular protozoan parasites in the phylum Apicomplexa. The apical complex is involved in attachment to and penetration of the host cell, and in parasite proliferation.

nodes.name: rhoptry
nodes.description: A large, club-shaped secretory organelle that forms part of the apical complex of an apicomplexan parasite, and consists of a bulbous body and a narrow electron-dense neck that extends through the conoid at the apical tip of the parasite. The rhoptry necks serve as ducts through which the contents of the rhoptries are secreted after attachment to the host has been completed and at the commencement of invasion. Rhoptry proteins function in the biogenesis and host organellar association of the parasitophorous vacuole.

nodes.name: conoid
nodes.description: A spiral cytoskeletal structure located at the apical end of the apical complex in some apicomplexan parasites. Fibers form a left-handed spiral, and are comprised of tubulin protofilaments organized in a ribbon-like structure that differs from the conventional tubular structure characteristic of microtubules.

nodes.name: ciliary pocket
nodes.description: Invagination of the plasma membrane from which a cilium (also called flagellum) protrudes.

nodes.name: kinetoplast
nodes.description: A sub-structure within the large single mitochondrion of kinetoplastid parasites and which is closely associated with the flagellar pocket and basal body of the flagellum.

nodes.name: antipodal site
nodes.description: The pole of the kinetoplast associated with kinetoplast DNA replication. The antipodal sites flank the kinetoplast DNA disk and are positioned approximately 180 degrees apart. In Trypanosoma brucei and Crithidia fasciculata, minicircles are attached at antipodal sites and they contain enzymes that catalyse some of the later reactions in minicircle replication.

nodes.name: polar ring of apical complex
nodes.description: An electron dense ring at the most anterior position of the apical complex, from which the conoid fibers originate; formed during an invasive life cycle stage of an apicomplexan parasite.

nodes.name: basal ring of apical complex
nodes.description: An electron dense ring at the most posterior position of the apical complex, from which the subpellicular microtubules originate; formed during an invasive life cycle stage of an apicomplexan parasite.

nodes.name: subpellicular network
nodes.description: A mechanically stable cytoskeletal structure associated with the cytoplasmic face of the pellicle and surrounding the microtubule-based cytoskeleton.

nodes.name: pellicle
nodes.description: The structure enclosing certain parasite cells such as certain apicomplexa and Euglenozoa; consists of the cell membrane with its associated infrastructure of microtubules, microfilaments and other organelles.

nodes.name: sarcomere
nodes.description: The repeating unit of a myofibril in a muscle cell, composed of an array of overlapping thick and thin filaments between two adjacent Z discs.

nodes.name: Z disc
nodes.description: Platelike region of a muscle sarcomere to which the plus ends of actin filaments are attached.

nodes.name: cell junction
nodes.description: A cellular component that forms a specialized region of connection between two or more cells, or between a cell and the extracellular matrix, or between two membrane-bound components of a cell, such as flagella.

nodes.name: synapse
nodes.description: The junction between an axon of one neuron and a dendrite of another neuron, a muscle fiber or a glial cell. As the axon approaches the synapse it enlarges into a specialized structure, the presynaptic terminal bouton, which contains mitochondria and synaptic vesicles. At the tip of the terminal bouton is the presynaptic membrane; facing it, and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft) is a specialized area of membrane on the receiving cell, known as the postsynaptic membrane. In response to the arrival of nerve impulses, the presynaptic terminal bouton secretes molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction
nodes.description: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction
nodes.description: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a post-synaptic potential responsible for muscle contraction.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction
nodes.description: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential that inhibits muscle contraction.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the inhibition of somatic muscle myotube contraction. Examples of somatic muscle myotubes include the somatic muscle cells of arthropods.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a myotube.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of somatic muscle myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle myotube, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cell.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the inhibition of somatic muscle myotube contraction. Examples of somatic muscle myotubes include the somatic muscle cells of arthropods.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of somatic muscle
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle cell, such as those found in nematodes and arthropods.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of somatic muscle myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle myotube, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cell.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the inhibition of somatic muscle myotube contraction. Examples of somatic muscle myotubes include the somatic muscle cells of arthropods.

nodes.name: excitatory synapse
nodes.description: A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell increases the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction
nodes.description: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a post-synaptic potential responsible for muscle contraction.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

nodes.name: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.

nodes.name: parallel fiber to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: An excitatory synapse formed by the parallel fibers of granule cells synapsing onto the dendrites of Purkinje cells.

nodes.name: asymmetric, glutamatergic, excitatory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse with a postsynaptic density, that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in excitatory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: cerebellar climbing fiber to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a climbing fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum. The climbing fiber originates from the inferior olivary nucleus of the medulla oblongata.

nodes.name: cerebellar granule cell to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a granule cell fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum.

nodes.name: inhibitory synapse
nodes.description: A synapse in which an action potential in the presynaptic cell reduces the probability of an action potential occurring in the postsynaptic cell.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction
nodes.description: The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential that inhibits muscle contraction.

nodes.name: inhibitory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the inhibition of somatic muscle myotube contraction. Examples of somatic muscle myotubes include the somatic muscle cells of arthropods.

nodes.name: symmetric, GABA-ergic, inhibitory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse that lacks an electron dense postsynaptic specialization, uses GABA as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: ribbon synapse
nodes.description: Type of synapse characterized by an electron-dense ribbon, lamella (bar) or spherical body in the presynaptic process cytoplasm.

nodes.name: cochlear hair cell ribbon synapse
nodes.description: A ribbon synpase of an auditory hair cell of the cochlear. These ribbon synapses contain spherical synaptic ribbons and lack and arciform density.

nodes.name: photoreceptor ribbon synapse
nodes.description: A ribbon synapse between a retinal photoreceptor cell (rod or cone) and a retinal bipolar cell. These contain a plate-like synaptic ribbon.

nodes.name: Schaffer collateral - CA1 synapse
nodes.description: A synapse between the Schaffer collateral axon of a CA3 pyramidal cell and a CA1 pyramidal cell.

nodes.name: glycinergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses glycine as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: dopaminergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses dopamine as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: noradrenergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses noradrenaline as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: glutamatergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: asymmetric, glutamatergic, excitatory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse with a postsynaptic density, that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in excitatory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: cerebellar climbing fiber to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a climbing fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum. The climbing fiber originates from the inferior olivary nucleus of the medulla oblongata.

nodes.name: cerebellar granule cell to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a granule cell fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum.

nodes.name: polyadic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse consisting of a single presynapse and multiple postsynapses. These postsynapses may come from the same cell of from different cells. Polyadic synapses are common in arthropod and nematode central nervous systems.

nodes.name: cholinergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses acetylcholine as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber
nodes.description: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.

nodes.name: GABA-ergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses GABA as a neurotransmitter. These synapses are typically inhibitory.

nodes.name: symmetric, GABA-ergic, inhibitory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse that lacks an electron dense postsynaptic specialization, uses GABA as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: neuron to neuron synapse
nodes.description: A synapse in which pre and post-synaptic cells are neurons.

nodes.name: asymmetric synapse
nodes.description: A type of synapse occurring between an axon and a dendritic spine or dendritic shaft. Asymmetric synapses, the most abundant synapse type in the central nervous system, involve axons that contain predominantly spherical vesicles and contain a thickened postsynaptic density. Most or all synapses of this type are excitatory.

nodes.name: mossy fiber rosette
nodes.description: A synapse of a mossy fiber onto the dendrite of a granule cell; each mossy fiber can have up to 50 rosettes.

nodes.name: asymmetric, glutamatergic, excitatory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse with a postsynaptic density, that uses glutamate as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in excitatory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: cerebellar climbing fiber to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a climbing fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum. The climbing fiber originates from the inferior olivary nucleus of the medulla oblongata.

nodes.name: cerebellar granule cell to Purkinje cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse of a granule cell fiber onto the dendrites of a Purkinje cell in cerebellum.

nodes.name: spine synapse
nodes.description: A type of synapse occurring between an axon and a dendritic spine.

nodes.name: symmetric synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that lacks an electron dense postsynaptic specialization. In vertebtrates, these occur primarily on dendrite shafts and neuronal cell bodies and involve persynapses containing clusters of predominantly flattened or elongated vesicles and are typcially inhibitory.

nodes.name: symmetric, GABA-ergic, inhibitory synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse that lacks an electron dense postsynaptic specialization, uses GABA as a neurotransmitter and whose activity results in inhibitory postsynaptic potentials.

nodes.name: hippocampal mossy fiber to CA3 synapse
nodes.description: One of the giant synapses that form between the mossy fiber axons of dentate gyrus granule cells and the large complex spines of CA3 pyramidal cells. It consists of a giant bouton known as the mossy fiber expansion, synapsed to the complex, multiheaded spine (thorny excresence) of a CA3 pyramidal cell.

nodes.name: serotonergic synapse
nodes.description: A synapse that uses serotonin as a neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: cerebellar Golgi cell to granule cell synapse
nodes.description: A synapse formed by a cerebellar Golgi cell synapsing on to a cerebellar granule cell.

nodes.name: perforant pathway to dendrate granule cell synapse
nodes.description: A neuron to neuron synapse of a pyramidal neuron in the entorhinal cortex onto a granule cell in the dentate gyrus of the hippocampus.

nodes.name: anchoring junction
nodes.description: A cell junction that mechanically attaches a cell (and its cytoskeleton) to neighboring cells or to the extracellular matrix.

nodes.name: cell-cell junction
nodes.description: A cell junction that forms a connection between two or more cells of an organism; excludes direct cytoplasmic intercellular bridges, such as ring canals in insects.

nodes.name: adherens junction
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction composed of the epithelial cadherin-catenin complex. The epithelial cadherins, or E-cadherins, of each interacting cell extend through the plasma membrane into the extracellular space and bind to each other. The E-cadherins bind to catenins on the cytoplasmic side of the membrane, where the E-cadherin-catenin complex binds to cytoskeletal components and regulatory and signaling molecules.

nodes.name: spot adherens junction
nodes.description: A small cell-cell adherens junction assembled during the cellularization stage of insect embyrogenesis; spot adherens junctions later fuse to form the zonula adherens.

nodes.name: zonula adherens
nodes.description: A cell-cell adherens junction which forms a continuous belt near the apex of epithelial cells.

nodes.name: puncta adhaerentia
nodes.description: A small version of the zonula adherens type junction, characterized by a symmetrical adherent point between two cells.

nodes.name: fascia adherens
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction that contains the transmembrane protein N-cadherin, which interacts with identical molecules from neighbouring cells to form a tight mechanical intercellular link; forms a large portion of the intercalated disc, the structure at which myofibrils terminate in cardiomyocytes.

nodes.name: gap junction
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction composed of pannexins or innexins and connexins, two different families of channel-forming proteins.

nodes.name: plasmodesma
nodes.description: A fine cytoplasmic channel, found in all higher plants, that connects the cytoplasm of one cell to that of an adjacent cell.

nodes.name: primary plasmodesma
nodes.description: A plasmodesma that consists of a simple, single channel; found predominantly in young tissue and formed as a function of cell plate formation during cytokinesis.

nodes.name: secondary plasmodesma
nodes.description: A plasmodesma with a branched structure, often with many channels leading into a larger central cavity; found in older tissues and usually derived from preexisting primary plasmodesmata.

nodes.name: desmosome
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction in which: on the cytoplasmic surface of each interacting plasma membrane is a dense plaque composed of a mixture of intracellular anchor proteins; a bundle of keratin intermediate filaments is attached to the surface of each plaque; transmembrane adhesion proteins of the cadherin family bind to the plaques and interact through their extracellular domains to hold the adjacent membranes together by a Ca2+-dependent mechanism.

nodes.name: paranodal junction
nodes.description: A highly specialized cell-cell junction found in vertebrates, which forms between a neuron and a glial cell, and has structural similarity to Drosophila septate junctions. It flanks the node of Ranvier in myelinated nerve and electrically isolates the myelinated from unmyelinated nerve segments and physically separates the voltage-gated sodium channels at the node from the cluster of potassium channels underneath the myelin sheath.

nodes.name: filtration diaphragm
nodes.description: A specialized cell-cell junction found between the cells of the excretory system, which provides a barrier for filtration of blood or hemolymph.

nodes.name: nephrocyte diaphragm
nodes.description: A specialized cell-cell junction found between nephrocytes of the insect kidney, which is adapted for filtration of hemolymph. The insect nephrocyte is anatomically and functionally similar to the glomerular podocyte of vertebrates.

nodes.name: slit diaphragm
nodes.description: A specialized cell-cell junction found between the interdigitating foot processes of the glomerular epithelium (the podocytes) in the vertebrate kidney, which is adapted for facilitating glomerular filtration.

nodes.name: apical junction complex
nodes.description: A functional unit located near the cell apex at the points of contact between epithelial cells, which in vertebrates is composed of the tight junction, the zonula adherens, and desmosomes and in some invertebrates, such as Drosophila, is composed of the subapical complex (SAC), the zonula adherens and the septate junction. Functions in the regulation of cell polarity, tissue integrity and intercellular adhesion and permeability.

nodes.name: cell-cell contact zone
nodes.description: Extended zone of intimate apposition between two cells containing one or more types of intercellular junctions, e.g., the intercalated disk of muscle.

nodes.name: intercalated disc
nodes.description: A complex cell-cell junction at which myofibrils terminate in cardiomyocytes; mediates mechanical and electrochemical integration between individual cardiomyocytes. The intercalated disc contains regions of tight mechanical attachment (fasciae adherentes and desmosomes) and electrical coupling (gap junctions) between adjacent cells.

nodes.name: peg and socket contact
nodes.description: A cell-cell contact zone that consists of membrane invaginations extending from either cell, which contain tight-, gap-, and adherens junctions. Peg and socket contacts form between endothelial cells and pericytes, and between lens fiber cells.

nodes.name: intercellular canaliculus
nodes.description: An extremely narrow tubular channel located between adjacent cells. An instance of this is the secretory canaliculi occurring between adjacent parietal cells in the gastric mucosa of vertebrates.

nodes.name: apical ectoplasmic specialization
nodes.description: Testis-specific junction between mature spermatids and Sertoli cells at the luminal end of the Sertoli cell.

nodes.name: basal ectoplasmic specialization
nodes.description: Testis-specific junction between mature Sertoli cells involved in establishing the blood-testis barrier of the Sertoli cell.

nodes.name: tight junction
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction that seals cells together in an epithelium in a way that prevents even small molecules from leaking from one side of the sheet to the other.

nodes.name: septate junction
nodes.description: A cell-cell junction that forms a continuous band around each cell in an epithelium; within the septate junction the membranes of adjacent cells maintain a constant distance of approximately 15 nm; found in arthropods.

nodes.name: pleated septate junction
nodes.description: A septate junction in which regular arrays of electron-dense septae span the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: smooth septate junction
nodes.description: A septate junction that lacks the regular arrays of electron-dense septae found in pleated septate junctions.

nodes.name: bicellular tight junction
nodes.description: An occluding cell-cell junction that is composed of a branching network of sealing strands that completely encircles the apical end of each cell in an epithelial sheet; the outer leaflets of the two interacting plasma membranes are seen to be tightly apposed where sealing strands are present. Each sealing strand is composed of a long row of transmembrane adhesion proteins embedded in each of the two interacting plasma membranes.

nodes.name: host-symbiont bicellular tight junction
nodes.description: An occluding cell-cell junction formed between the membranes of the apical end of an invading cell (e.g. a merozoite in Plasmodium) and a host target cell (e.g. erythrocyte for Plasmodium infection). The junction is a stable yet dynamic structure that moves around the symbiont cell during invasion, enclosing it in a vacuole surrounded by a membrane.

nodes.name: tricellular tight junction
nodes.description: An specialized occluding junction where three epithelial cells meet. It is composed of a branching network of sealing strands that run perpendicularly to the bicellular tight junction at the point of contact between three epithelial cells in an epithelial sheet.

nodes.name: cell-substrate junction
nodes.description: A cell junction that forms a connection between a cell and the extracellular matrix.

nodes.name: focal adhesion
nodes.description: A cell-substrate junction that anchors the cell to the extracellular matrix and that forms a point of termination of actin filaments. In insects focal adhesion has also been referred to as hemi-adherens junction (HAJ).

nodes.name: muscle tendon junction
nodes.description: A cell-substrate junction found at the terminal anchorage site of skeletal muscle cells to tendons.

nodes.name: hemidesmosome
nodes.description: A cell-substrate junction (attachment structure) found in epithelial cells that links intermediate filaments to extracellular matrices via transmembrane complexes. In vertebrates, hemidesmosomes mediate contact between the basal side of epithelial cells and the basal lamina. In C. elegans, hemidesmosomes connect epithelial cells to distinct extracellular matrices on both the apical and basal cell surfaces.

nodes.name: flagellum attachment zone
nodes.description: A network of cytoskeletal and membranous connections responsible for the lateral attachment of the cilium to the cell body in some trypanosomatid species.

nodes.name: flagella connector
nodes.description: A mobile transmembrane junction at the tip of the flagellum of some kinetoplastid species linking the tip of a new growing flagellum to an older flagellum.

nodes.name: mitochondrial crista
nodes.description: Any of the inward folds of the mitochondrial inner membrane. Their number, extent, and shape differ in mitochondria from different tissues and organisms. They appear to be devices for increasing the surface area of the mitochondrial inner membrane, where the enzymes of electron transport and oxidative phosphorylation are found. Their shape can vary with the respiratory state of the mitochondria.

nodes.name: external encapsulating structure
nodes.description: A structure that lies outside the plasma membrane and surrounds the entire cell or cells. This does not include the periplasmic space.

nodes.name: cell wall
nodes.description: The rigid or semi-rigid envelope lying outside the cell membrane of plant, fungal, most prokaryotic cells and some protozoan parasites, maintaining their shape and protecting them from osmotic lysis. In plants it is made of cellulose and, often, lignin; in fungi it is composed largely of polysaccharides; in bacteria it is composed of peptidoglycan; in protozoan parasites such as Giardia species, it's made of carbohydrates and proteins.

nodes.name: peptidoglycan-based cell wall
nodes.description: A protective structure outside the cytoplasmic membrane composed of peptidoglycan (also known as murein), a molecule made up of a glycan (sugar) backbone of repetitively alternating N-acetylglucosamine and N-acetylmuramic acid with short, attached, cross-linked peptide chains containing unusual amino acids. An example of this component is found in Escherichia coli.

nodes.name: Gram-positive-bacterium-type cell wall
nodes.description: A layer of peptidoglycan found outside of the cytoplasmic membrane. The peptidoglycan is relatively thick (20-80nm) and retains the primary stain of the Gram procedure, thus cells appear blue after Gram stain. The cell walls often contain teichoic acids (acidic anionic polysaccharides) bound to the peptidoglycan. Examples of this component are found in Gram-positive bacteria.

nodes.name: Gram-negative-bacterium-type cell wall
nodes.description: The peptidoglycan layer of the Gram-negative cell envelope. In Gram-negative cells the peptidoglycan is relatively thin (1-2nm) and is linked to the outer membrane by lipoproteins. In Gram-negative cells the peptidoglycan is too thin to retain the primary stain in the Gram staining procedure and therefore cells appear red after Gram stain.

nodes.name: fungal-type cell wall
nodes.description: A rigid yet dynamic structure surrounding the plasma membrane that affords protection from stresses and contributes to cell morphogenesis, consisting of extensively cross-linked glycoproteins and carbohydrates. The glycoproteins may be modified with N- or O-linked carbohydrates, or glycosylphosphatidylinositol (GPI) anchors; the polysaccharides are primarily branched glucans, including beta-linked and alpha-linked glucans, and may also include chitin and other carbohydrate polymers, but not cellulose or pectin. Enzymes involved in cell wall biosynthesis are also found in the cell wall. Note that some forms of fungi develop a capsule outside of the cell wall under certain circumstances; this is considered a separate structure.

nodes.name: ascospore wall
nodes.description: The specialized cell wall of the ascospore (spore), which is the product of meiotic division. Examples of this component are found in Fungi.

nodes.name: yeast-form cell wall
nodes.description: The wall surrounding a cell of a dimorphic fungus growing in the single-cell budding yeast form, in contrast to the filamentous or hyphal form.

nodes.name: hyphal cell wall
nodes.description: The cell wall surrounding a fungal hypha.

nodes.name: plant-type cell wall
nodes.description: A more or less rigid stucture lying outside the cell membrane of a cell and composed of cellulose and pectin and other organic and inorganic substances.

nodes.name: primary cell wall
nodes.description: A plant cell wall that is still able to expand, permitting cell growth. Primary cell walls contain more pectin than secondary walls and no lignin is present.

nodes.name: secondary cell wall
nodes.description: A plant cell wall that is no longer able to expand and so does not permit growth. Secondary cell walls contain less pectin that primary cell walls. The secondary cell is mostly composed of cellulose and is strengthened with lignin.

nodes.name: spore wall
nodes.description: The specialized envelope lying outside the cell membrane of a spore.

nodes.name: ascospore wall
nodes.description: The specialized cell wall of the ascospore (spore), which is the product of meiotic division. Examples of this component are found in Fungi.

nodes.name: endospore external encapsulating structure
nodes.description: The structures that lie outside the inner membrane and surround the entire endospore; consists of a peptidoglycan-containing inner layer (the endospore cortex) surrounded by a multilayered proteinaceous coat. An exosporium may be present as an extreme outer layer.

nodes.name: sexual spore wall
nodes.description: A specialized envelope lying outside the cell membrane of a spore derived from a product of meiosis.

nodes.name: asexual spore wall
nodes.description: A specialized envelope lying outside the cell membrane of a spore derived from an asexual process. Examples of this process are found in bacterial and fungal species.

nodes.name: cyst wall
nodes.description: The specialized envelope lying outside the cell membrane of a cyst. A cyst is a resting or dormant stage of a microorganism, usually a bacterium or a protist or rarely an invertebrate animal, that helps the organism to survive in unfavorable environmental conditions. In protists such as protozoan parasites alternating cystic- and non-cystic stages, the cyst wall is usually composed of carbohydrates and proteins.

nodes.name: glycocalyx
nodes.description: A carbohydrate rich layer at the outermost periphery of a cell.

nodes.name: slime layer
nodes.description: A slime layer is an easily removed, diffuse, unorganized layer of extracellular material that surrounds a cell. Specifically this consists mostly of exopolysaccharides, glycoproteins, and glycolipids.

nodes.name: capsule
nodes.description: A protective structure surrounding some fungi and bacteria, attached externally to the cell wall and composed primarily of polysaccharides. Capsules are highly organized structures that adhere strongly to cells and cannot be easily removed. Capsules play important roles in pathogenicity, preventing phagocytosis by other cells, adherance, and resistance to dessication.

nodes.name: lysosomal glycocalyx
nodes.description: The polysaccharide-based coating on the inner side of a lysosomal membrane. It may be involved in protecting the membrane from digestion by lysosomal enzymes.

nodes.name: stereocilium coat
nodes.description: A glycocalyx on the the endolymphatic surface of a cochlear hair cell that coats the external surface of each stereocilium and maintains a small distance between adjacent stereocilia in the bundle.

nodes.name: sperm glycocalyx
nodes.description: The carbohydrate rich layer at the outermost periphery of a sperm cell.

nodes.name: platelet glycocalyx
nodes.description: The carbohydrate rich layer at the outermost periphery of a platelet.

nodes.name: vascular endothelial glycocalyx
nodes.description: The carbohydrate-rich layer lining the vascular endothelium connected to the endothelium through a variety of molecules, mainly proteoglycans and glycoproteins. These form a network in which soluble molecules, either plasma- or endothelium-derived, are incorporated.

nodes.name: S-layer
nodes.description: A crystalline protein layer surrounding some bacteria.

nodes.name: extracellular matrix
nodes.description: A structure lying external to one or more cells, which provides structural support, biochemical or biomechanical cues for cells or tissues.

nodes.name: middle lamella
nodes.description: Layer of intercellular material, chiefly pectic substances, cementing together the primary walls of contiguous cells.

nodes.name: egg coat
nodes.description: A specialized extracellular matrix that surrounds the plasma membrane of the ovum of animals. The egg coat provides structural support and can play an essential role in oogenesis, fertilization and early development.

nodes.name: fertilization envelope
nodes.description: A structure that lies outside the plasma membrane and surrounds the egg. The fertilization envelope forms from the vitelline membrane after fertilization as a result of cortical granule release.

nodes.name: vitelline envelope
nodes.description: A glycoprotein-based structure that lies outside the plasma membrane and surrounds the egg before fertilization.

nodes.name: pollen coat
nodes.description: A layer of extracellular matrix deposited onto the surface of the pollen wall upon disintegration of the tapetal layer of the anther wall in the late stages of pollen development. The composition of this material is highly heterogeneous and includes waxes, lipid droplets, small aromatic molecules, and proteins. The pollen coat is proposed to have many functions, such as holding pollen in the anther until dispersal, facilitation of pollen dispersal, protection of pollen from water loss and UV radiation, and facilitation of adhesion of pollen to the stigma.

nodes.name: organomineral extracellular matrix
nodes.description: An extracellular matrix consisting of a densely packed organomineral assembly in which the mineral phase represents the majority of the material by weight.

nodes.name: collagen-containing extracellular matrix
nodes.description: An extracellular matrix consisting mainly of proteins (especially collagen) and glycosaminoglycans (mostly as proteoglycans) that provides not only essential physical scaffolding for the cellular constituents but can also initiate crucial biochemical and biomechanical cues required for tissue morphogenesis, differentiation and homeostasis. The components are secreted by cells in the vicinity and form a sheet underlying or overlying cells such as endothelial and epithelial cells.

nodes.name: basement membrane
nodes.description: A collagen-containing extracellular matrix consisting of a thin layer of dense material found in various animal tissues interposed between the cells and the adjacent connective tissue. It consists of the basal lamina plus an associated layer of reticulin fibers.

nodes.name: interstitial matrix
nodes.description: A type of extracellular matrix found in interstitial connective tissue, characterized by the presence of fibronectins, proteoglycans, and types I, III, V, VI, VII and XII collagens.

nodes.name: interphotoreceptor matrix
nodes.description: A specialized extracellularc matrix that surrounds the photoreceptors of the retina and lies between them and the apical surface of the retinal pigment epithelium. The IPM has been implicated in several important activities required for photoreceptor function and maintenance.

nodes.name: hyaline layer
nodes.description: A multilayered extraembryonic matrix that functions as a substrate for cell adhesion through early development. It is thought to protect and lubricate the embryo, stabilize the blastomeres during morphogenesis, and regulate nutrient intake. The major constituent of the hyaline layer is the protein hyalin. This matrix has been found in echinoderms.

nodes.name: collagen and cuticulin-based cuticle extracellular matrix
nodes.description: A collagen and cuticulin-based noncellular, multilayered structure that is synthesized by an underlying ectodermal (hypodermal) cell layer. The cuticle serves essential functions in body morphology, locomotion, and environmental protection. An example of this component is found in Caenorhabditis elegans.

nodes.name: extracellular matrix of synaptic cleft
nodes.description: The portion of the extracellular matrix that lies within the synaptic cleft.

nodes.name: perisynaptic extracellular matrix
nodes.description: The portion of the extracellular matrix that lies within the perisynaptic space.

nodes.name: perineuronal net
nodes.description: A dense extracellular matrix (ECM) that forms around many neuronal cell bodies and dendrites late in development and is responsible for synaptic stabilization in the adult brain.

nodes.name: synapse-associated extracellular matrix
nodes.description: The extracellular matrix of the perisynaptic space (the extracellular space adjacent to the synapse) and the synaptic cleft.

nodes.name: biofilm matrix
nodes.description: A structure lying external to microbial cells. A biofilm is an aggregate of surface-associated cells, and the biofilm matrix is the envelope of polymeric substances that surrounds the cells.

nodes.name: bacterial biofilm matrix
nodes.description: A structure lying external to bacterial cells. A biofilm is an aggregate of surface-associated bacteria, and the biofilm matrix is the envelope of polymeric substances that surrounds the bacteria.

nodes.name: fungal biofilm matrix
nodes.description: An extracellular matrix lying external to fungal cells. The fungal biofilm matrix consists of polysaccharides, proteins, lipids, and nucleic acids. Fungal biofilms mediate adherence to host tissues, and provide protection from host immune defenses.

nodes.name: adhesive extracellular matrix
nodes.description: A extracellular matrix which attaches an organism to a substrate.

nodes.name: chitin-based extracellular matrix
nodes.description: Any constituent part of a chitin-based noncellular, hardened, or membranous extracellular matrix secreted from the apical surface of an epithelial sheet.

nodes.name: egg chorion
nodes.description: A protective, noncellular membrane that surrounds the eggs of various animals including insects and fish.

nodes.name: pollen wall
nodes.description: The wall surrounding a mature pollen grain; a multilayered structure consisting of a pectocellulosic intine surrounded by a sporopollenin-based exine, which itself contains two layers, the inner nexine and the outer sexine.

nodes.name: T-tubule
nodes.description: Invagination of the plasma membrane of a muscle cell that extends inward from the cell surface around each myofibril. The ends of T-tubules make contact with the sarcoplasmic reticulum membrane.

nodes.name: site of polarized growth
nodes.description: Any part of a cell where non-isotropic growth takes place.

nodes.name: hyphal tip
nodes.description: The end, or tip, of a fungal hypha, where polarized growth occurs during hyphal elongation.

nodes.name: cellular bud tip
nodes.description: The end of a cellular bud distal to the site of attachment to the mother cell.

nodes.name: cellular bud neck
nodes.description: The constriction between the mother cell and daughter cell (bud) in an organism that reproduces by budding.

nodes.name: growth cone
nodes.description: The migrating motile tip of a growing neuron projection, where actin accumulates, and the actin cytoskeleton is the most dynamic.

nodes.name: dendritic growth cone
nodes.description: The migrating motile tip of a growing nerve cell dendrite.

nodes.name: axonal growth cone
nodes.description: The migrating motile tip of a growing nerve cell axon.

nodes.name: growing cell tip
nodes.description: The region at either end of the longest axis of a cylindrical or elongated cell, where polarized growth occurs.

nodes.name: old growing cell tip
nodes.description: A cell tip which has existed for at least one complete cell cycle, and at which polarized growth occurs. For example, in fission yeast the cell end that existed prior to cell division grows immediately after division, and contains a distinctive complement of proteins including actin cytoskeletal structures.

nodes.name: old cell tip after activation of bipolar cell growth
nodes.description: A cell tip which has existed for at least one complete cell cycle, and at which polarized growth occurs, which is part of a cell that has activated bipolar cell growth (i.e. in which new end take-off, NETO, has taken place). For example, in fission yeast the cell end that existed prior to cell division grows immediately after division, and contains a distinctive complement of proteins including actin cytoskeletal structures.

nodes.name: new growing cell tip
nodes.description: A cell tip that was newly formed at the last cell division, and that has started to grow after the cell has activated bipolar cell growth (i.e. in which new end take-off, NETO, has taken place). New end take-off is when monopolar cells initiate bipolar growth.

nodes.name: pollen tube tip
nodes.description: The region at growing end of the pollen tube cell, where polarized growth occurs.

nodes.name: mating projection tip
nodes.description: The apex of the mating projection in unicellular fungi exposed to mating pheromone; site of polarized growth.

nodes.name: cell septum
nodes.description: A structure composed of peptidoglycan and often chitin in addition to other materials. It usually forms perpendicular to the long axis of a cell or hypha and grows centripetally from the cell wall to the center of the cell and often functions in the compartmentalization of a cell into two daughter cells.

nodes.name: adventitious septum
nodes.description: A cell septum whose formation is independent of nuclear division.

nodes.name: porous cell septum
nodes.description: A septum or cross wall which does not entirely span the space between two portions of cell wall and may contain a specialized central pore structure. A porous septum allows the movement of organelles and/or cytoplasm between compartments.

nodes.name: dolipore septum
nodes.description: A septum, or cross-wall, between two portions of a cell or hypha; contains a central pore around which the septum is swollen to form a barrel-shaped structure; pore is covered on each side of the septum by a septal pore cap (parenthosome).

nodes.name: division septum
nodes.description: A cell septum which forms as part of the division site and functions in the compartmentalization of a cell into two daughter cells at division. A division septum spans a cell and does not allow exchange of organelles or cytoplasm between compartments.

nodes.name: primary cell septum
nodes.description: A cell septum that forms following nuclear division.

nodes.name: secondary cell septum
nodes.description: Cell wall structures composed of linear polysaccharides which are deposited at both sides of the primary septum at 90 degrees to the primary septum.

nodes.name: actin cap
