nodes.description: Polarized accumulation of cytoskeletal proteins (including F-actin) and regulatory proteins in a cell. An example of this is the actin cap found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

nodes.name: smooth muscle dense body
nodes.description: Electron-dense region associated with a smooth muscle contractile fiber.

nodes.name: midbody
nodes.description: A thin cytoplasmic bridge formed between daughter cells at the end of cytokinesis. The midbody forms where the contractile ring constricts, and may persist for some time before finally breaking to complete cytokinesis.

nodes.name: bacterial-type flagellum basal body, rod
nodes.description: The central portion of the bacterial-type flagellar basal body, which spans the periplasm and threads through the rings.

nodes.name: nucleolar chromatin
nodes.description: The portion of nuclear chromatin associated with the nucleolus; includes the DNA encoding the ribosomal RNA.

nodes.name: nucleolus organizer region
nodes.description: A region of a chromosome where nucleoli form during interphase, and where genes encoding the largest rRNA precursor transcript are tandemly arrayed.

nodes.name: nucleolus-associated heterochromatin
nodes.description: Dense particles of heterochromatin, consisting of a loosely twisted strand about 600 Angstrom thick, found associated with the nucleolus.

nodes.name: rDNA protrusion
nodes.description: Any of the tandem arrays of rDNA localized at the periphery of the nucleus and protruding into the nucleolus, and associated proteins. May be visible as a single or double spot by DAPI staining.

nodes.name: cell leading edge
nodes.description: The area of a motile cell closest to the direction of movement.

nodes.name: growth cone leading edge
nodes.description: That part of the growth cone which represents the distal part of the structure.

nodes.name: leading edge of axonal growth cone
nodes.description: That part of the axonal growth cone which represents the distal part of the structure.

nodes.name: leading edge of dendritic growth cone
nodes.description: That part of the dendritic growth cone which represents the distal part of the structure.

nodes.name: leading edge of lamellipodium
nodes.description: That part of the lamellipodium which represents the distal part of the structure.

nodes.name: cell trailing edge
nodes.description: The area of a motile cell opposite to the direction of movement.

nodes.name: leading edge membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the leading edge of a motile cell.

nodes.name: lamellipodium membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a lamellipodium.

nodes.name: ruffle membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a ruffle.

nodes.name: neuron projection membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a neuron projection.

nodes.name: axolemma
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding an axon; it is a specialized trilaminar random mosaic of protein molecules floating within a fluid matrix of highly mobile phospholipid molecules, 7-8 nm in thickness.

nodes.name: dendrite membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendrite.

nodes.name: dendritic spine membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a dendritic spine.

nodes.name: stereocilium membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a stereocilium.

nodes.name: cell trailing edge membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding the trailing edge of a motile cell.

nodes.name: uropod membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a uropod.

nodes.name: M band
nodes.description: The midline of aligned thick filaments in a sarcomere; location of specific proteins that link thick filaments. Depending on muscle type the M band consists of different numbers of M lines.

nodes.name: centrosomal corona
nodes.description: An amorphous structure surrounding the core of the centrosome, from which microtubules are nucleated; contains gamma-tubulin.

nodes.name: A band
nodes.description: The dark-staining region of a sarcomere, in which myosin thick filaments are present; the center is traversed by the paler H zone, which in turn contains the M line.

nodes.name: H zone
nodes.description: A relatively pale zone traversing the center of the A band of a sarcomere, visible in relaxed muscle fibers; consists of the central portion of thick (myosin) filaments that are not overlapped by thin (actin) filaments.

nodes.name: I band
nodes.description: A region of a sarcomere that appears as a light band on each side of the Z disc, comprising a region of the sarcomere where thin (actin) filaments are not overlapped by thick (myosin) filaments; contains actin, troponin, and tropomyosin; each sarcomere includes half of an I band at each end.

nodes.name: cytostome
nodes.description: Stable, specialized structure for the ingestion of food by the cell into phagosomes.

nodes.name: cytoproct
nodes.description: Stable, specialized structure for extrusion of waste by the cell into the surrounding medium.

nodes.name: oral apparatus
nodes.description: Complex basket- or funnel-like structure used by the cell to collect food and channel it to the cytostome; includes specialized sub-structures made up of closely-spaced cilia and underlying basal bodies and fibrillar systems.

nodes.name: membrane-enclosed lumen
nodes.description: The enclosed volume within a sealed membrane or between two sealed membranes. Encompasses the volume enclosed by the membranes of a particular organelle, e.g. endoplasmic reticulum lumen, or the space between the two lipid bilayers of a double membrane surrounding an organelle, e.g. nuclear envelope lumen.

nodes.name: organelle lumen
nodes.description: The internal volume enclosed by the membranes of a particular organelle; includes the volume enclosed by a single organelle membrane, e.g. endoplasmic reticulum lumen, or the volume enclosed by the innermost of the two lipid bilayers of an organelle envelope, e.g. nuclear lumen.

nodes.name: vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane or protein that forms a vesicle.

nodes.name: cytoplasmic vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a cytoplasmic vesicle.

nodes.name: plasma membrane-derived thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.

nodes.name: aleurone grain lumen

nodes.name: synaptic vesicle lumen

nodes.name: secretory granule lumen

nodes.name: platelet dense granule lumen

nodes.name: platelet alpha granule lumen

nodes.name: chromaffin granule lumen

nodes.name: azurophil granule lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an azurophil granule, a primary lysosomal granule found in neutrophil granulocytes that contains a wide range of hydrolytic enzymes and is released into the extracellular fluid.

nodes.name: specific granule lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a specific granule, a granule with a membranous, tubular internal structure, found primarily in mature neutrophil cells. Most are released into the extracellular fluid. Specific granules contain lactoferrin, lysozyme, vitamin B12 binding protein and elastase.

nodes.name: acrosomal lumen

nodes.name: spine apparatus lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the spine apparatus membrane.

nodes.name: cytolytic granule lumen
nodes.description: Any cytoplasmic membrane-bounded vesicle lumen that is part of a cytolytic granule.

nodes.name: COPI-coated vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a COPI-coated endocytic vesicle.

nodes.name: COPII-coated vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a COPII-coated endocytic vesicle.

nodes.name: phagolysosome vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a phagolysosome.

nodes.name: multivesicular body, internal vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of the multivesicular body internal vesicle.

nodes.name: rhoptry lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the rhoptry membrane.

nodes.name: intracellular organelle lumen
nodes.description: An organelle lumen that is part of an intracellular organelle.

nodes.name: mitochondrial matrix
nodes.description: The gel-like material, with considerable fine structure, that lies in the matrix space, or lumen, of a mitochondrion. It contains the enzymes of the tricarboxylic acid cycle and, in some organisms, the enzymes concerned with fatty acid oxidation.

nodes.name: vacuolar lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the vacuolar membrane.

nodes.name: fungal-type vacuole lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the vacuolar membrane of a vacuole, the shape of which correlates with cell cycle phase. An example of this structure is found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae.

nodes.name: plant-type vacuole lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the vacuolar membrane of a vacuole that retains the same shape regardless of cell cycle phase. An example of this is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.

nodes.name: protein storage vacuole lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the protein storage vacuole membrane.

nodes.name: autophagosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the autophagosome double-membrane.

nodes.name: azurophil granule lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an azurophil granule, a primary lysosomal granule found in neutrophil granulocytes that contains a wide range of hydrolytic enzymes and is released into the extracellular fluid.

nodes.name: lysosomal lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the lysosomal membrane.

nodes.name: endolysosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an endolysosome. An endolysosome is a transient hybrid organelle formed by fusion of a late endosome with a lysosome.

nodes.name: acrosomal lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the acrosome membrane.

nodes.name: cytolytic granule lumen
nodes.description: Any cytoplasmic membrane-bounded vesicle lumen that is part of a cytolytic granule.

nodes.name: phagolysosome vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a phagolysosome.

nodes.name: autolysosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume that is enclosed within the autolysosome single-membrane.

nodes.name: endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: sarcoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the sarcoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: longitudinal sarcoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the longitudinal sarcoplasmic reticulum envelope. The longitudinal sarcoplasmic reticulum lumen is continuous with the lumen contained within the terminal cisternae.

nodes.name: terminal cisterna lumen
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the terminal cisterna envelope. This space is enriched in calsequestrin.

nodes.name: rough endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the rough endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: smooth endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the smooth endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: perinuclear endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the perinuclear endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: cortical endoplasmic reticulum lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the cortical endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: Golgi lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of any cisterna or subcompartment of the Golgi apparatus, including the cis- and trans-Golgi networks.

nodes.name: Golgi stack lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by any of the membranes of the thin, flattened cisternae that form the central portion of the Golgi complex.

nodes.name: trans-Golgi network transport vesicle lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed within the membrane of a trans-Golgi network transport vesicle.

nodes.name: platelet dense tubular network lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of the platelet dense tubular network.

nodes.name: endosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an endosome.

nodes.name: early endosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an early endosome.

nodes.name: late endosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a late endosome.

nodes.name: multivesicular body lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the outermost membrane of a multivesicular body.

nodes.name: recycling endosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of a recycling endosome.

nodes.name: endolysosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of an endolysosome. An endolysosome is a transient hybrid organelle formed by fusion of a late endosome with a lysosome.

nodes.name: microbody lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of a microbody.

nodes.name: peroxisomal matrix
nodes.description: The volume contained within the membranes of a peroxisome; in many cells the matrix contains a crystalloid core largely composed of urate oxidase.

nodes.name: glyoxysomal lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of a glyoxysome.

nodes.name: glycosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membrane of a glycosome.

nodes.name: organelle envelope lumen
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of an organelle envelope.

nodes.name: nuclear envelope lumen
nodes.description: The region between the two lipid bilayers of the nuclear envelope; 20-40 nm wide.

nodes.name: mitochondrial intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the mitochondrial envelope.

nodes.name: plastid intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the plastid envelope.

nodes.name: chloroplast intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of a chloroplast envelope.

nodes.name: chromoplast intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of a chromoplast envelope.

nodes.name: cyanelle intermembrane space
nodes.description: The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the cyanelle envelope; includes the peptidoglycan layer.

nodes.name: nuclear lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the nuclear inner membrane.

nodes.name: acidocalcisome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the membranes of an acidocalcisome.

nodes.name: hydrogenosome lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the hydrogenosome membrane.

nodes.name: microneme lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by the microneme membrane.

nodes.name: gut granule lumen
nodes.description: The lumen of a gut granule, a lysosome-related organelle contained within the intestinal cells of the nematode C. elegans.

nodes.name: envelope
nodes.description: A multilayered structure surrounding all or part of a cell; encompasses one or more lipid bilayers, and may include a cell wall layer; also includes the space between layers.

nodes.name: cell envelope
nodes.description: An envelope that surrounds a bacterial cell and includes the cytoplasmic membrane and everything external, encompassing the periplasmic space, cell wall, and outer membrane if present.

nodes.name: organelle envelope
nodes.description: A double membrane structure enclosing an organelle, including two lipid bilayers and the region between them. In some cases, an organelle envelope may have more than two membranes.

nodes.name: nuclear envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the nucleus and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space, a gap of width 20-40 nm (also called the perinuclear space).

nodes.name: mitochondrial envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the mitochondrion and separating its contents from the cell cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: plastid envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing a plastid and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: chloroplast envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the chloroplast and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: chromoplast envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the chromoplast and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: amyloplast envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the amyloplast and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: cyanelle envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the cyanelle and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: etioplast envelope
nodes.description: The double lipid bilayer enclosing the etioplast and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space.

nodes.name: spindle envelope
nodes.description: An organelle envelope that surrounds the chromosomes and the central part of the spindle apparatus during mitosis and meiosis; observed in many invertebrates. The spindle envelope consists of membrane layers, called parafusorial membranes, derived from endoplasmic reticulum membrane; in male meiosis it forms during prometaphase and persists until early in the ensuing interphase.

nodes.name: thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a thylakoid membrane.

nodes.name: plastid thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a plastid thylakoid membrane.

nodes.name: chloroplast thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The cavity enclosed within the chloroplast thylakoid membrane. An example of this component is found in Arabidopsis thaliana.

nodes.name: cyanelle thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a cyanelle thylakoid membrane.

nodes.name: plasma membrane-derived thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by a plasma membrane-derived thylakoid.

nodes.name: organellar chromatophore thylakoid lumen
nodes.description: The volume enclosed by an organellar chromatophore thylakoid membrane.

nodes.name: organelle subcompartment
nodes.description: A compartment that consists of a lumen and an enclosing membrane, and is part of an organelle.

nodes.name: micropexophagy-specific membrane apparatus
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded flattened sac that is formed during micropexophagy between the membrane tips of an engulfing vacuole, completing the engulfment and sequestration of peroxisomes from the cytosol, and forming a micropexophagic body within the lumen of the vacuole.

nodes.name: Golgi apparatus subcompartment
nodes.description: A compartment that consists of a lumen and an enclosing membrane, and is part of the Golgi apparatus.

nodes.name: Golgi stack
nodes.description: The set of thin, flattened membrane-bounded compartments, called cisternae, that form the central portion of the Golgi complex. The stack usually comprises cis, medial, and trans cisternae; the cis- and trans-Golgi networks are not considered part of the stack.

nodes.name: trans-Golgi network
nodes.description: The network of interconnected tubular and cisternal structures located within the Golgi apparatus on the side distal to the endoplasmic reticulum, from which secretory vesicles emerge. The trans-Golgi network is important in the later stages of protein secretion where it is thought to play a key role in the sorting and targeting of secreted proteins to the correct destination.

nodes.name: Golgi cisterna
nodes.description: Any of the thin, flattened membrane-bounded compartments that form the central portion of the Golgi complex.

nodes.name: Golgi cis cisterna
nodes.description: The Golgi cisterna closest to the endoplasmic reticulum; the first processing compartment through which proteins pass after export from the ER.

nodes.name: Golgi trans cisterna
nodes.description: The Golgi cisterna farthest from the endoplasmic reticulum; the final processing compartment through which proteins pass before exiting the Golgi apparatus; the compartment in which N-linked protein glycosylation is completed.

nodes.name: Golgi medial cisterna
nodes.description: The middle Golgi cisterna (or cisternae).

nodes.name: endoplasmic reticulum subcompartment
nodes.description: A distinct region of the endoplasmic reticulum.

nodes.name: terminal cisterna
nodes.description: The portion of sarcoplasmic reticulum devoted to calcium ion storage and calcium ion release.

nodes.name: subrhabdomeral cisterna
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded compartment that is found at the base of the rhabdomere and contains stored calcium, InsP3 receptors and smooth endoplasmic reticulum Ca2+-ATPase.

nodes.name: endoplasmic reticulum cisternal network
nodes.description: A subcompartment of the endoplasmic reticulum consisting of flattened, disc-shaped domains known as cisternae. These are typically found close to the nucleus and are generally more prominent in secretory cells.

nodes.name: endoplasmic reticulum tubular network
nodes.description: A subcompartment of the endoplasmic reticulum consisting of tubules having membranes with high curvature in cross-section.

nodes.name: cortical endoplasmic reticulum
nodes.description: A cortical network of highly dynamic tubules that are juxtaposed to the plasma membrane and undergo ring closure and tubule-branching movements.

nodes.name: deep fiber
nodes.description: Inward projections of the cytoskeletal structures of the oral apparatus, which form a fiber that extends past the cytostome into the cytoplasm.

nodes.name: eisosome
nodes.description: A cell part that is composed of the eisosome membrane or MCC domain, a furrow-like plasma membrane sub-domain and associated integral transmembrane proteins, and the proteins (eisosome filaments) that form a scaffolding lattice on the cytoplasmic face. Eisosomes broadly affect overall plasma membrane organization.

nodes.name: cell division site
nodes.description: The eventual plane of cell division (also known as cell cleavage or cytokinesis) in a dividing cell. In Eukaryotes, the cleavage apparatus, composed of septin structures and the actomyosin contractile ring, forms along this plane, and the mitotic, or meiotic, spindle is aligned perpendicular to the division plane. In bacteria, the cell division site is generally located at mid-cell and is the site at which the cytoskeletal structure, the Z-ring, assembles.

nodes.name: septin band
nodes.description: A diffuse ring composed of a series of septin bars that run parallel to the long axis of the cell. This type of septin structure has been observed in a number of locations associated with polarized grown and/or deposition of new membrane, but not with cytokinesis, such as at the shmoo (mating projection) neck, at the junction between the mother cell and the germ tube (hypha) of a fungal cell growing filamentously.

nodes.name: mating projection septin band
nodes.description: A septin band, i.e. a diffuse ring composed of a series of septin bars running parallel to the long axis of the cell, located at the neck of a shmoo (mating projection).

nodes.name: hyphal septin band
nodes.description: A septin band, i.e. a diffuse ring composed of a series of septin bars running parallel to the long axis of the cell, located at the junction between the mother cell and the germ tube (hypha) of a fungal cell growing filamentously.

nodes.name: cleavage apparatus septin structure
nodes.description: Any of a series of structures composed of septins and septin-associated proteins localized to the cleavage plane which are involved in cytokinesis.

nodes.name: cellular bud neck septin ring
nodes.description: A ring-shaped structure that forms at the site of cytokinesis in the bud neck of a budding cell; composed of members of the conserved family of filament forming proteins called septins as well as septin-associated proteins. In S. cerevisiae, this structure forms at the time of bud emergence and the septins show a high rate of exchange.

nodes.name: prospore septin ring
nodes.description: A tight ring-shaped structure that forms in the division plane at the site of cytokinesis in a prospore; composed of septins as well as septin-associated proteins.

nodes.name: cellular bud neck septin collar
nodes.description: A tubular structure with flared ends, shaped like an hourglass and composed of highly ordered arrays of septin filaments, that forms at the bud neck of a dividing cell. In S. cerevisiae, this structure is located at the bud neck throughout most of the cell cycle and the septins are fixed within the structure, not exchanging with soluble septins. This septin structure acts as a scaffold for other proteins that function at the bud neck.

nodes.name: cellular bud neck split septin rings
nodes.description: Two separate septin rings that are formed from the septin collar at the time of cytokinesis in cells that divide by budding. These two rings are thought to delineate a special compartment in which factors involved in cytokinesis are concentrated.

nodes.name: medial cortex septin ring
nodes.description: A ring-shaped structure that forms at the medial cortex of a symmetrically dividing cell at the onset of cytokinesis; composed of members of the conserved family of filament forming proteins called septins as well as septin-associated proteins.

nodes.name: medial membrane band
nodes.description: A sterol-rich region of the plasma membrane which forms at the cell surface overlying the contractile ring and spreads into the invaginating plasma membrane surrounding the septum.

nodes.name: germ tube
nodes.description: The slender tubular outgrowth first produced by most spores in germination.

nodes.name: stereocilium tip
nodes.description: A distinct compartment at the tip of a stereocilium, distal to the site of attachment to the apical cell surface. It consists of a dense matrix bridging the barbed ends of the stereocilium actin filaments with the overlying plasma membrane, is dynamic compared to the shaft, and is required for stereocilium elongation.

nodes.name: actin filament bundle
nodes.description: An assembly of actin filaments that are on the same axis but may be oriented with the same or opposite polarities and may be packed with different levels of tightness.

nodes.name: actin rod
nodes.description: A cellular structure consisting of parallel, hexagonally arranged actin tubules, comprising filamentous actin and associated proteins. Actin rod structures are found in diverse organisms, having been observed in spores of Dictyostelium discoideum, Drosophila melanogaster oocytes, as well as in numerous animal cells under stress conditions.

nodes.name: cofilin-actin rod
nodes.description: A cellular structure consisting of parallel, hexagonally arranged actin tubules, comprising filamentous actin and disulfide cross-linked cofilin multimers.

nodes.name: actin tubule
nodes.description: A cellular structure, approximately 13 nm in diameter, consisting of three actin filaments bundled together.

nodes.name: contractile actin filament bundle
nodes.description: An actin filament bundle in which the filaments are loosely packed (approximately 30-60 nm apart) and arranged with opposing polarities; the loose packing allows myosin (usually myosin-II) to enter the bundle.

nodes.name: stress fiber
nodes.description: A contractile actin filament bundle that consists of short actin filaments with alternating polarity, cross-linked by alpha-actinin and possibly other actin bundling proteins, and with myosin present in a periodic distribution along the fiber.

nodes.name: parallel actin filament bundle
nodes.description: An actin filament bundle in which the filaments are tightly packed (approximately 10-20 nm apart) and oriented with the same polarity.

nodes.name: formin-nucleated actin cable
nodes.description: An actin filament bundle that consists of short filaments organized into bundles of uniform polarity, and is nucleated by formins. In fungal cells, myosin motors transport cargo along actin cables toward sites of polarized cell growth; actin cables may play a similar role in pollen tube growth.

nodes.name: actin filament bundle of actin-based cell projection
nodes.description: A bundle of cross-linked actin filaments that is part of an actin-based cell protrusion, in which filaments are oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which stabilizes the filaments.

nodes.name: microvillar actin bundle
nodes.description: A parallel bundle of actin filaments at the core of a microvillus.

nodes.name: actin filament bundle of stereocilium
nodes.description: A bundle of hundreds of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), that is the supporting structure of a stereocilium. Filaments are oriented such that the the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion and are capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma membrane.

nodes.name: actin filament bundle of filopodium
nodes.description: A parallel bundle of actin filaments that is part of filopodium. Filaments are oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex.

nodes.name: filopodium tip
nodes.description: The end of a filopodium distal to the body of the cell.

nodes.name: cuticular plate
nodes.description: A dense network of actin filaments found beneath the apical cell surface of hair cells, and into which stereocilia are inserted.

nodes.name: apical lamina of hyaline layer
nodes.description: A fibrous network that is part of the hyalin layer extracellular matrix. The apical lamina is thought to be principally composed of the glycoproteins fibropellins. This matrix has been found in echinoderms.

nodes.name: growth cone membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a growth cone.

nodes.name: porosome
nodes.description: A permanent cup-shaped structure at the cell plasma membrane in secretory cells. Following a secretory stimulus, secretory vesicles transiently dock and fuse at the base of porosomes and release intravesicular contents dictated by the turgor pressure generated from the swelling of secretory vesicles.

nodes.name: cellular bud membrane
nodes.description: The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a cellular bud.

nodes.name: cytoskeletal calyx
nodes.description: A large cytoskeletal structure located at the posterior end of the perinuclear theca of a mammalian sperm head. The nucleus is tightly associated with the calyx, which contains calicin and basic cylicin proteins.

nodes.name: gas vesicle shell
nodes.description: The proteinaceous structure surrounding a gas vesicle.

nodes.name: node of Ranvier
nodes.description: An axon part that is a gap in the myelin where voltage-gated sodium channels cluster and saltatory conduction is executed.

nodes.name: internode region of axon
nodes.description: An axon part that is located between the nodes of Ranvier and surrounded by compact myelin sheath.

nodes.name: paranode region of axon
nodes.description: An axon part that is located adjacent to the nodes of Ranvier and surrounded by lateral loop portions of myelin sheath.

nodes.name: basal labyrinth
nodes.description: A region in the lower half of some cells formed from extensive infoldings of the basal plasma membrane; includes cytoplasm adjacent to the infolded membrane.

nodes.name: nuclear periphery
nodes.description: The portion of the nuclear lumen proximal to the inner nuclear membrane.

nodes.name: centriolar satellite
nodes.description: A small (70-100 nm) cytoplasmic granule that contains a number of centrosomal proteins; centriolar satellites traffic toward microtubule minus ends and are enriched near the centrosome.

nodes.name: organelle-enclosing lipid monolayer
nodes.description: A lipid monolayer that surrounds and encloses an organelle.

nodes.name: chlorosome envelope
nodes.description: The structure, composed of a monolayer of glycolipids with embedded proteins, that encloses the pigments and other contents of the chlorosome.

nodes.name: monolayer-surrounded lipid storage body outer lipid monolayer
nodes.description: The single layer of phopholipids surrounding a lipid storage body.

nodes.name: microtubule organizing center attachment site
nodes.description: A region of the nuclear envelope to which a microtubule organizing center (MTOC) attaches; protein complexes embedded in the nuclear envelope mediate direct or indirect linkages between the microtubule cytoskeleton and the nuclear envelope.

nodes.name: female germline ring canal outer rim
nodes.description: An electron opaque backbone of the insect ovarian ring canal that is a part of or adjacent to the plasma membrane. The outer rim is established as the cleavage furrow is arrested, and contains F-actin, anillin, glycoproteins and at least one a protein with a high content of phosphorylated tyrosine residues.

nodes.name: female germline ring canal inner rim
nodes.description: A proteinaceous actin-rich layer of the insect ovarian ring canal that forms subcortically to the outer rim. The electron dense inner rim accumulates after the final mitotic division of each germline syncytia, and contains actin, a phosphotyrosine protein, and a number of cytoskeletal proteins.

nodes.name: ciliary rootlet
nodes.description: A cytoskeleton-like structure, originating from the basal body at the proximal end of a cilium, and extending proximally toward the cell nucleus. Rootlets are typically 80-100 nm in diameter and contain cross striae distributed at regular intervals of approximately 55-70 nm.

nodes.name: sperm fibrous sheath
nodes.description: A cytoskeletal structure surrounding the axoneme and outer dense fibers of the sperm flagellum. Consists of two longitudinal columns connected by closely arrayed semicircular ribs that assemble from distal to proximal throughout spermiogenesis. The fibrous sheath probably influences the degree of flexibility, plane of flagellar motion, and the shape of the flagellar beat.

nodes.name: myelin sheath abaxonal region
nodes.description: The region of the myelin sheath furthest from the axon.

nodes.name: myelin sheath adaxonal region
nodes.description: The region of the myelin sheath nearest to the axon.

nodes.name: endonuclear canal
nodes.description: A membrane-bound structure present in the nucleus of a spermatozoon. There is variation in the number of endonuclear canals between sperm of different organisms, and some species lack these structures altogether. The endonuclear canal may provide a supporting role for the sperm nucleus, and originates during spermiogenesis from an invagination of the nuclear envelope.

nodes.name: ciliary transition zone
nodes.description: A region of the cilium between the basal body and proximal segment that is characterized by Y-shaped assemblages that connect axonemal microtubules to the ciliary membrane. The ciliary transition zone appears to function as a gate that controls ciliary membrane composition and separates the cytosol from the ciliary plasm.

nodes.name: photoreceptor connecting cilium
nodes.description: The portion of the photoreceptor cell cilium linking the photoreceptor inner and outer segments. It's considered to be equivalent to the ciliary transition zone.

nodes.name: scintillon
nodes.description: A body present in the cytoplasm of some dinoflagellates, which is the source of bioluminescence; emits light on acidification in the presence of oxygen.

nodes.name: acroblast
nodes.description: A cone-shaped structure in the head of a spermatozoon, which is formed by the coalescence of Golgi fragments following the completion of meiosis. The acroblast is situated adjacent to the acrosomal vesicle.

nodes.name: hyaluranon cable
nodes.description: A cable structure, surrounding some cell types (e.g. proximal or bronchial tubular epithelial cells), and composed of hyaluranon (HA), a ubiquitous connective tissue glycosaminoglycan.

nodes.name: pairing center
nodes.description: A special chromosome region located towards one end of a chromosome that contains dispersed copies of short, repetitive DNA sequences and functions as a cis-acting element essential for presynaptic homologous chromosome pairing and chromosome-nuclear envelope attachment.

nodes.name: myofilament
nodes.description: Any of the smallest contractile units of a myofibril (striated muscle fiber).

nodes.name: striated muscle myosin thick filament
nodes.description: Bipolar filaments formed of polymers of a muscle-specific myosin II isoform, found in the middle of sarcomeres in myofibrils.

nodes.name: striated muscle thin filament
nodes.description: Filaments formed of actin and associated proteins; attached to Z discs at either end of sarcomeres in myofibrils.

nodes.name: keratohyalin granule
nodes.description: A cytoplasmic, non-membrane bound granule of, at least, keratinocyte. Associated to keratin intermediate filaments and partially crosslinked to the cell envelope.

nodes.name: somatodendritic compartment
nodes.description: The region of a neuron that includes the cell body (cell soma) and dendrite(s), but excludes the axon.

nodes.name: glycogen granule
nodes.description: Cytoplasmic bead-like structures of animal cells, visible by electron microscope. Each granule is a functional unit with the biosynthesis and catabolism of glycogen being catalyzed by enzymes bound to the granule surface.

nodes.name: periplasmic space
nodes.description: The region between the inner (cytoplasmic) and outer membrane (Gram-negative Bacteria) or cytoplasmic membrane and cell wall (Fungi and Gram-positive Bacteria).

nodes.name: cell wall-bounded periplasmic space
nodes.description: The region between the plasma membrane and the cell wall in organisms lacking an outer cell membrane such as yeast and Gram positive bacteria. The region is thinner than the equivalent in Gram negative bacteria.

nodes.name: outer membrane-bounded periplasmic space
nodes.description: The region between the inner (cytoplasmic or plasma) membrane and outer membrane of organisms with two membranes such as Gram negative bacteria. These periplasmic spaces are relatively thick and contain a thin peptidoglycan layer (PGL), also referred to as a thin cell wall.

nodes.name: septal periplasm
nodes.description: The region between the plasma membrane and the cell wall, as found in organisms such as filamentous fungi.

nodes.name: actomyosin
nodes.description: Any complex of actin, myosin, and accessory proteins.

nodes.name: stress fiber
nodes.description: A contractile actin filament bundle that consists of short actin filaments with alternating polarity, cross-linked by alpha-actinin and possibly other actin bundling proteins, and with myosin present in a periodic distribution along the fiber.

nodes.name: plasma membrane-derived chromatophore
nodes.description: A pigment-bearing structure that is derived from the cytoplasmic membrane, sometimes consisting of simple invaginations and sometimes a complete vesicle. This component is found in certain photosynthetic bacteria and cyanobacteria.

nodes.name: xanthophore
nodes.description: A chromatophore containing yellow pigment.

nodes.name: yolk granule
nodes.description: Discrete structures that partition the water-insoluble portion of the yolk of oocytes and ova, which may or may not be membrane enclosed.

nodes.name: intracellular immature spore
nodes.description: A cell or part of the cell that constitutes an early developmental stage of a spore, a small reproductive body that is highly resistant to desiccation and heat and is capable of growing into a new organism, produced especially by certain bacteria, fungi, algae, and nonflowering plants.

nodes.name: endospore-forming forespore
nodes.description: Portion of the cell formed during the process of bacterial sporulation that will ultimately become the core of the endospore. An endospore is a type of dormant cell that is resistant to adverse conditions.

nodes.name: ascospore-type prospore
nodes.description: An immature spore undergoing development. The spore usually consists of nucleic acid, prospore membrane(s) that encase the nucleic acid, and ultimately a cell wall that covers the membrane(s). This type of spore is observed in ascospore-forming fungi.

nodes.name: cell projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon.

nodes.name: bacterial-type flagellum
nodes.description: A motor complex composed of an extracellular helical protein filament coupled to a rotary motor embedded in the cell envelope.

nodes.name: periplasmic flagellum
nodes.description: Flagellar filaments located in the periplasmic space; characterized in spirochetes, in which they are essential for shape and motility. Composed of a core surrounded by two sheath layers, the flagella rotate to allow migration of the cell through viscous media, which would not be possible using external flagella.

nodes.name: pilus
nodes.description: A proteinaceous hair-like appendage on the surface of bacteria ranging from 2-8 nm in diameter.

nodes.name: type IV pilus
nodes.description: A short filamentous structure on the surface of a bacterial cell distinguished from other pili by post-translational N-methylation of the pilin monomers.

nodes.name: curli
nodes.description: A proteinaceous extracellular fiber, produced by an enteric bacterium, that is involved in surface and cell-cell contacts that promote community behavior and host colonization.

nodes.name: type I pilus
nodes.description: A short filamentous structure on the surface of a bacterial cell distinguished from other pili by their D-mannose-sensitive agglutinatination of erythrocytes. In E. coli, type I pili consist of a short tip fibrillum made up of the adhesin protein (FimH) and two minor subunits (FimG and FimF) that is joined to the pilus rod, a homopolymer of ~1000 FimA subunits.

nodes.name: haustorium
nodes.description: A projection from a cell or tissue that penetrates the host's cell wall and invaginates the host cell membrane.

nodes.name: arbuscule
nodes.description: Highly branched symbiont haustoria within host root cortex cells, responsible for nutrient exchange.

nodes.name: plant cell papilla
nodes.description: A cell projection that is a short, rounded projection from a plant epidermal cell.

nodes.name: leaf papilla
nodes.description: A plant cell papilla that is part of a leaf papilla cell.

nodes.name: stigma papilla
nodes.description: A plant cell papilla that is part of a stigma papilla cell.

nodes.name: trichome papilla
nodes.description: A plant cell papilla that is part of a trichome cell.

nodes.name: archaeal-type flagellum
nodes.description: A non-membrane-bounded organelle superficially similar to a bacterial-type flagellum; they both consist of filaments extending outside the cell, and rotate to propel the cell, but the archaeal flagella (also called archaella) have a unique structure which lacks a central channel. Similar to bacterial type IV pilins, the archaeal flagellins (archaellins) are made with class 3 signal peptides and they are processed by a type IV prepilin peptidase-like enzyme. The archaellins are typically modified by the addition of N-linked glycans which are necessary for proper assembly and/or function.

nodes.name: plasma membrane bounded cell projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a cell and that is bounded by plasma membrane, e.g. a cilium, lamellipodium, or axon.

nodes.name: ruffle
nodes.description: Projection at the leading edge of a crawling cell; the protrusions are supported by a microfilament meshwork.

nodes.name: uropod
nodes.description: A membrane projection with related cytoskeletal components at the trailing edge of a cell in the process of migrating or being activated, found on the opposite side of the cell from the leading edge or immunological synapse, respectively.

nodes.name: cilium
nodes.description: A specialized eukaryotic organelle that consists of a filiform extrusion of the cell surface and of some cytoplasmic parts. Each cilium is largely bounded by an extrusion of the cytoplasmic (plasma) membrane, and contains a regular longitudinal array of microtubules, anchored to a basal body.

nodes.name: motile cilium
nodes.description: A cilium which may have a variable arrangement of axonemal microtubules and also contains molecular motors. It may beat with a whip-like pattern that promotes cell motility or transport of fluids and other cells across a cell surface, such as on epithelial cells that line the lumenal ducts of various tissues; or they may display a distinct twirling motion that directs fluid flow asymmetrically across the cellular surface to affect asymmetric body plan organization. Motile cilia can be found in single as well as multiple copies per cell.

nodes.name: 9+0 motile cilium
nodes.description: A motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets but no central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+0 axoneme).

nodes.name: 9+2 motile cilium
nodes.description: A motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets plus two central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+2 axoneme).

nodes.name: sperm flagellum
nodes.description: A microtubule-based flagellum (or cilium) that is part of a sperm, a mature male germ cell that develops from a spermatid.

nodes.name: left anterior flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It originates at the left anterior basal body, extends laterally through the cytoplasm, crosses the right anterior axoneme, and exits as a membrane-bound flagellum on the anterior left side of the cell.

nodes.name: right anterior flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It originates at the right anterior basal body, extends laterally through the cytoplasm, crosses the left anterior axoneme, and exits as a membrane-bound flagellum on the anterior right side of the cell.

nodes.name: left posteriolateral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left posteriolateral basal body and extends cytoplasmically toward the cell posterior, marking the left anterior boundary of the lateral shield and the left lateral region of the funis before exiting at the left lateral region of the cell body.

nodes.name: right posteriolateral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right posteriolateral basal body and extends cytoplasmically toward the cell posterior, marking the right anterior boundary of the lateral shield and the right lateral region of the funis before exiting at the right lateral region of the cell body.

nodes.name: left ventral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left ventral basal body and exits the cell body proximally and dorsal to the ventral disc.

nodes.name: right ventral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right ventral basal body and exits the cell body proximally and dorsal to the ventral disc.

nodes.name: left caudal flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left caudal basal body, extending cytoplasmically and exiting at the posterior end of the cell body.

nodes.name: right caudal flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right caudal basal body, extending cytoplasmically and exiting at the posterior end of the cell body.

nodes.name: transverse flagellum
nodes.description: A motile cilium found in dinoflagellates. It coils around the cell and provides the forward thrust for motility. It is often contained in a furrow called the cingulum, and emerges from a flagellar pore located in the cingulum.

nodes.name: longitudinal flagellum
nodes.description: A motile cilium found in dinoflagellates. It trails the cell and acts as a steering rudder. It is often partially contained in a furrow called the sulcus, and emerges from a flagellar pore located in the sulcus.

nodes.name: non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A cilium which may have a variable array of axonemal microtubules but does not contain molecular motors.

nodes.name: 9+0 non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A non-motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets but no central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+0 axoneme).

nodes.name: photoreceptor cell cilium
nodes.description: A specialised 9+0 non-motile cilium found in photoreceptor cells. A ciliary transition zone called 'photoreceptor connecting cilium' links the photoreceptor outer segment to the inner segment.

nodes.name: 9+2 non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A non-motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets plus two central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+2 axoneme).

nodes.name: kinocilium
nodes.description: A nonmotile primary cilium that is found at the apical surface of auditory receptor cells. The kinocilium is surrounded by actin-based stereocilia.

nodes.name: mating projection
nodes.description: The projection formed by unicellular fungi in response to mating pheromone.

nodes.name: rhabdomere
nodes.description: The specialized microvilli-containing organelle on the apical surfaces of a photoreceptor cell containing the visual pigment rhodopsin and most of the proteins involved in phototransduction.

nodes.name: lamellipodium
nodes.description: A thin sheetlike process extended by the leading edge of a migrating cell or extending cell process; contains a dense meshwork of actin filaments.

nodes.name: growth cone lamellipodium
nodes.description: A thin sheetlike process extended by the leading edge of an axonal or dendritic growth cone; contains a dense meshwork of actin filaments.

nodes.name: pseudopodium
nodes.description: A temporary protrusion or retractile process of a cell, associated with flowing movements of the protoplasm, and serving for locomotion and feeding.

nodes.name: bleb
nodes.description: A cell extension caused by localized decoupling of the cytoskeleton from the plasma membrane and characterized by rapid formation, rounded shape, and scarcity of organelles within the protrusion. Blebs are formed during apoptosis and other cellular processes, including cell locomotion, cell division, and as a result of physical or chemical stresses.

nodes.name: cytoneme
nodes.description: A long, thin, polarized cell projection that contains actin and can extend for distances many times the diameter of the cell. Cytonemes represent extensions of cell cytoplasm and typically have a diameter of approximately 0.2um.

nodes.name: root hair
nodes.description: A long, thin projection from a root epidermal cell that contains F-actin and tubulin, and a cell wall.

nodes.name: muscle cell projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a muscle cell. A muscle cell is a mature contractile cell, commonly known as a myocyte. This cell has as part of its cytoplasm myofibrils organized in various patterns.

nodes.name: neuron projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a nerve cell, e.g. an axon or dendrite.

nodes.name: axon
nodes.description: The long process of a neuron that conducts nerve impulses, usually away from the cell body to the terminals and varicosities, which are sites of storage and release of neurotransmitter.

nodes.name: giant axon
nodes.description: Extremely large, unmyelinated axon found in invertebrates. Has high conduction speeds and is usually involved in panic or escape responses.

nodes.name: C-fiber
nodes.description: The axon of a dorsal root ganglion cell that are responsive to pain and temperature. C-fibers are small in diameter (0.2-1.5 um) and unmyelinated.

nodes.name: cerebellar mossy fiber
nodes.description: An axon arising from cerebellar projecting cells in the cochlea, vestibular nuclei, spinal cord, reticular formation, cerebellar nuclei and basilar pontine nuclei. Mossy fibers enter through all three cerebellar peduncles and send collaterals to the deep cerebellar nuclei, then branch in the white matter and terminate in the granule cell layer. Through this branching, a given mossy fiber can innervate several folia. Mossy fibers synapse on granule cells. The synaptic contacts are made at enlargements along the length of the mossy fiber called mossy fiber rosettes. The enlargements of the rosettes give the axons a mossy-looking appearance in Golgi stained preparations.

nodes.name: climbing fiber
nodes.description: The axon of inferior olive neuron that projects to the cerebellar cortex, largely via the inferior cerebellar peduncle. They range in diameter from 1-3 um and are myelinated until they enter the granule cell layer. They give off collaterals to the deep cerebellar nuclei. They synapse extensively with the dendrites of Purkinje cells in the molecular layer, where each fiber branches repeatedly to climb along the Purkinje cell dendritic tree. Each Purkinje cell is innervated by only a single climbing fiber.

nodes.name: hippocampal mossy fiber
nodes.description: An axon of a hippocampal granule cell, including dentate gyrus granule cell and CA3 granule cell, characterized by expansions (mossy fiber expansions) giving the fibers a mossy appearance. These unmyelinated axons were first described by Ramon y Cajal.

nodes.name: dentate gyrus mossy fiber
nodes.description: Hippocampal mossy fiber produced by dentate gyrus granule cells.

nodes.name: parallel fiber
nodes.description: A parallel fiber results from the bifurcation of a cerebellar granule cell axon in the molecular layer into two diametrically opposed branches, that are oriented parallel to the long axis of the folium.

nodes.name: dendrite
nodes.description: A neuron projection that has a short, tapering, morphology. Dendrites receive and integrate signals from other neurons or from sensory stimuli, and conduct nerve impulses towards the axon or the cell body. In most neurons, the impulse is conveyed from dendrites to axon via the cell body, but in some types of unipolar neuron, the impulse does not travel via the cell body.

nodes.name: dendritic branch
nodes.description: A dendrite arising from another dendrite.

nodes.name: sensory dendrite
nodes.description: A dendrite that is found on a sensory neuron, and directly transduces a sensory signal from the sensory neuron to another neuron.

nodes.name: apical dendrite
nodes.description: A dendrite that emerges near the apical pole of a neuron. In bipolar neurons, apical dendrites are located on the opposite side of the soma from the axon.

nodes.name: apical distal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the apical pole of a neuron, and which is farthest away from the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: apical proximal dendrite
nodes.description: The dendrite of the dendritic tree, which emerges near the apical pole of a neuron, and which is the closest to the cell body of the neuron (the soma).

nodes.name: basal dendrite
nodes.description: A dendrite that emerges near the basal pole of a neuron. In bipolar neurons, basal dendrites are either on the same side of the soma as the axon, or project toward the axon.

nodes.name: basal distal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the basal pole of a neuron (e.g. in bipolar neurons, basal dendrites are either on the same side of the soma as the axon, or project toward the axon), and which is farthest away from the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: basal proximal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the basal pole of a neuron (e.g. in bipolar neurons, basal dendrites are either on the same side of the soma as the axon, or project toward the axon), and which is the closest to the cell body of the neuron (the soma).

nodes.name: CA3 pyramidal cell dendrite
nodes.description: A dendrite of a hippocampal CA3 pyramidal cell.

nodes.name: primary dendrite
nodes.description: A dendrite emerging from the cell body (the soma) of a neuron.

nodes.name: distal dendrite
nodes.description: The dendrite of the dendritic tree that is farthest away from the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: apical distal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the apical pole of a neuron, and which is farthest away from the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: basal distal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the basal pole of a neuron (e.g. in bipolar neurons, basal dendrites are either on the same side of the soma as the axon, or project toward the axon), and which is farthest away from the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: proximal dendrite
nodes.description: The dendrite of the dendritic tree that is closest to the neuronal cell body (the soma).

nodes.name: apical proximal dendrite
nodes.description: The dendrite of the dendritic tree, which emerges near the apical pole of a neuron, and which is the closest to the cell body of the neuron (the soma).

nodes.name: basal proximal dendrite
nodes.description: Any dendrite in a dendritic tree that emerges near the basal pole of a neuron (e.g. in bipolar neurons, basal dendrites are either on the same side of the soma as the axon, or project toward the axon), and which is the closest to the cell body of the neuron (the soma).

nodes.name: stereocilium
nodes.description: An actin-based protrusion from the apical surface of auditory and vestibular hair cells and of neuromast cells. These protrusions are supported by a bundle of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma. Bundles of stereocilia act as mechanosensory organelles.

nodes.name: neuron spine
nodes.description: A small membranous protrusion, often ending in a bulbous head and attached to the neuron by a narrow stalk or neck.

nodes.name: dendritic spine
nodes.description: A small, membranous protrusion from a dendrite that forms a postsynaptic compartment, typically receiving input from a single presynapse. They function as partially isolated biochemical and an electrical compartments. Spine morphology is variable:they can be thin, stubby, mushroom, or branched, with a continuum of intermediate morphologies. They typically terminate in a bulb shape, linked to the dendritic shaft by a restriction. Spine remodeling is though to be involved in synaptic plasticity.

nodes.name: thorny excrescence
nodes.description: Large complex spine protruding from a dendrite. Each excrescence is formed by a cluster of spine heads.

nodes.name: axonal spine
nodes.description: A spine that originates from the axon, usually from the initial segment.

nodes.name: somatic spine
nodes.description: Spine emanating from the cell soma of a neuron.

nodes.name: rod spherule
nodes.description: A specialized neuron projection which is the site of synaptic transmission produced by retinal rod cells. Rod spherules are small round enlargements of the axon (3-5 micrometers diameter) or even extensions of the cell body.

nodes.name: kinocilium
nodes.description: A nonmotile primary cilium that is found at the apical surface of auditory receptor cells. The kinocilium is surrounded by actin-based stereocilia.

nodes.name: cell body fiber
nodes.description: A neuron projection that is found in unipolar neurons and corresponds to the region between the cell body and the point at which the single projection branches.

nodes.name: dendritic tree
nodes.description: The entire complement of dendrites for a neuron, consisting of each primary dendrite and all its branches.

nodes.name: Lewy neurite
nodes.description: Elongated neuronal process, often with side branches and more than one branching point, described in brains of patients with Parkinson's disease. Lewy neurites stain positively for ubiquitin in brainstem and forebrain regions affected in Parkinson's disease.

nodes.name: gemmule
nodes.description: Spine-like process found on some neurons, e.g., periglomerular cells of olfactory cortex.

nodes.name: photoreceptor cell cilium
nodes.description: A specialised 9+0 non-motile cilium found in photoreceptor cells. A ciliary transition zone called 'photoreceptor connecting cilium' links the photoreceptor outer segment to the inner segment.

nodes.name: dendritic filopodium
nodes.description: A small, membranous protrusion found primarily on dendritic stretches of developing neurons. May receive synaptic input, and can develop into dendritic spines.

nodes.name: growth cone lamellipodium
nodes.description: A thin sheetlike process extended by the leading edge of an axonal or dendritic growth cone; contains a dense meshwork of actin filaments.

nodes.name: proximal neuron projection
nodes.description: The portion of an axon or dendrite that is close to the neuronal cell body.

nodes.name: growth cone filopodium
nodes.description: A thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of an axonal or dendritic growth cone.

nodes.name: accessory outer segment
nodes.description: A cilium-like cell projection emanating from the inner segment and running alongside the outer segment of photoreceptors.

nodes.name: telodendria
nodes.description: Telodendria are projections that originate from the axon pedicle and form gap junctions with other neurons.

nodes.name: cone telodendria
nodes.description: Cone telodendria are projections that originate from the cone pedicle and form gap junctions with other photoreceptors within the outer plexiform layer of the retina.

nodes.name: rod telodendria
nodes.description: Rod telodendria are projections that originate from the rod pedicle and form gap junctions with other photoreceptors within the outer plexiform layer of the retina.

nodes.name: microspike
nodes.description: A dynamic, actin-rich projection extending from the surface of a migrating animal cell.

nodes.name: cell hair
nodes.description: A long, thin cell projection that contains F-actin and tubulin, with microtubules centrally located and F-actin peripherally located.

nodes.name: macropinocytic cup
nodes.description: A cell projection that forms at the site of macropinocytosis, a form of endocytosis that results in the uptake of relatively large amounts of extracellular fluid. The macropinocytic cup membrane selectively excludes certain proteins, such as H36 or PM4C4 in Dictyostelium, and the underlying cytoskeleton is enriched in F-actin and coronin.

nodes.name: pollen tube
nodes.description: A tubular cell projection that is part of a pollen tube cell and extends from a pollen grain.

nodes.name: glial cell projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from a glial cell.

nodes.name: capitate projection
nodes.description: Simple or compound process of epithelial glial cells with a spherical head that inserts into photoreceptor axons. Capitate projections have only been observed in Brachycera (flies).

nodes.name: astrocyte projection
nodes.description: A prolongation or process extending from the soma of an astrocyte and wrapping around neurons.

nodes.name: astrocyte end-foot
nodes.description: Terminal process of astrocyte abutting non-neuronal surfaces in the brain.

nodes.name: glial limiting end-foot
nodes.description: Terminal process of astrocyte that extends to the surface of the central nervous system. Together, glial limiting end-feet form the glial limiting membrane or glia limitans.

nodes.name: Schwann cell microvillus
nodes.description: Small finger-like extension of a Schwann cell that contacts the nodal membrane.

nodes.name: spiny bracelet of Nageotte
nodes.description: Paranodal terminations of Schwann cells that do not directly contact the paranodal axon membrane. Usually found in thicker myelin.

nodes.name: terminal loop
nodes.description: Portion of myelin-forming Schwann cell consisting of terminal cytoplasmic extensions adhered to the axon at the beginning and end of the myelin sheath.

nodes.name: dendritic cell dendrite
nodes.description: A branched cellular projection (or cytoplasmic extension) that is extended from the surface of a dendritic immune cell, and which enables the cell to sample luminal pathogens and increase the surface area for antigen presentation to T cells.

nodes.name: podocyte foot
nodes.description: A cell projection of a podocyte (glomerular visceral epithelial cell) forming a foot-like structure projecting from a podocyte primary projection, that wraps around capillaries of a renal glomerulus. Adjacent feet (pedicels) interdigitate, leaving thin filtration slits between them, which are covered by slit diaphragms.

nodes.name: podocyte primary projection
nodes.description: A cell projection originating from a renal glomerular podocyte and extending to the renal glomerular podocyte foot.

nodes.name: actin-based cell projection
nodes.description: A cell projection supported by an assembly of actin filaments, and which lacks microtubules.

nodes.name: microvillus
nodes.description: Thin cylindrical membrane-covered projections on the surface of an animal cell containing a core bundle of actin filaments. Present in especially large numbers on the absorptive surface of intestinal cells.

nodes.name: rhabdomere microvillus
nodes.description: Thin cylindrical membrane-covered projection on the surface of a rhabdomere.

nodes.name: Schwann cell microvillus
nodes.description: Small finger-like extension of a Schwann cell that contacts the nodal membrane.

nodes.name: filopodium
nodes.description: Thin, stiff, actin-based protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal or dendritic growth cone, or a dendritic shaft.

nodes.name: dendritic filopodium
nodes.description: A small, membranous protrusion found primarily on dendritic stretches of developing neurons. May receive synaptic input, and can develop into dendritic spines.

nodes.name: growth cone filopodium
nodes.description: A thin, stiff protrusion extended by the leading edge of an axonal or dendritic growth cone.

nodes.name: stereocilium
nodes.description: An actin-based protrusion from the apical surface of auditory and vestibular hair cells and of neuromast cells. These protrusions are supported by a bundle of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma. Bundles of stereocilia act as mechanosensory organelles.

nodes.name: dinoflagellate peduncle
nodes.description: A small, flexible, finger-like projection of cytoplasm containing an array of microtubles and located near the flagellar pores in some photosynthetic as well as nonphotosynthetic dinoflagellate species. Its functions are not fully understood, but it has been associated with feeding behavior (phagotrophy).

nodes.name: telopode
nodes.description: A telopode is a plasma membrane bounded cell projection that is present on a telocyte and is tens to hundreds of microns long. Telopodes form a labyrinthine system communicating through gap junctions.

nodes.name: costamere
nodes.description: Regular periodic sub membranous arrays of vinculin in skeletal and cardiac muscle cells, these arrays link Z-discs to the sarcolemma and are associated with links to extracellular matrix.

nodes.name: starch grain
nodes.description: Plant storage body for amylose and amylopectin, 1-100um in diameter. Also contains small amounts of enzymes, amino acids, lipids and nucleic acids. The shape of the grain varies widely amongst species, but is often spherical or disk-shaped.

nodes.name: amyloplast starch grain
nodes.description: Plant storage body for amylose and amylopectin, 1-100um in diameter, and located in amyloplasts. Also contains small amounts of enzymes, amino acids, lipids and nucleic acids. The shape of the grain varies widely amongst species, but is often spherical or disk-shaped.

nodes.name: chloroplast starch grain
nodes.description: Plant storage body for amylose and amylopectin, 1-100um in diameter, and located in chloroplasts. Also contains small amounts of enzymes, amino acids, lipids and nucleic acids. The shape of the grain varies widely amongst species, but is often spherical or disk-shaped.

nodes.name: acrosomal matrix
nodes.description: A structural framework, or 'dense core' at the interior of an acrosome. May regulate the distribution of hydrolases within the acrosome and their release during the acrosome reaction.

nodes.name: cell septum edging
nodes.description: The cell wall material that surrounds the septum in fungal cells.

nodes.name: axon initial segment
nodes.description: Portion of the axon proximal to the neuronal cell body, at the level of the axon hillock. The action potentials that propagate along the axon are generated at the level of this initial segment.

nodes.name: varicosity
nodes.description: Non-terminal inflated portion of the axon, containing the specialized apparatus necessary to release neurotransmitters.

nodes.name: dendritic shaft
nodes.description: Cylindric portion of the dendrite, directly stemming from the perikaryon, and carrying the dendritic spines.

nodes.name: axon hillock
nodes.description: Portion of the neuronal cell soma from which the axon originates.

nodes.name: perikaryon
nodes.description: The portion of the cell soma (neuronal cell body) that excludes the nucleus.

nodes.name: myelin sheath
nodes.description: An electrically insulating fatty layer that surrounds the axons of many neurons. It is an outgrowth of glial cells: Schwann cells supply the myelin for peripheral neurons while oligodendrocytes supply it to those of the central nervous system.

nodes.name: compact myelin
nodes.description: The portion of the myelin sheath in which layers of cell membrane are tightly juxtaposed, completely excluding cytoplasm. The juxtaposed cytoplasmic surfaces form the major dense line, while the juxtaposed extracellular surfaces form the interperiod line visible in electron micrographs.

nodes.name: lateral loop
nodes.description: Non-compact myelin located adjacent to the nodes of Ranvier in a myelin segment. These non-compact regions include cytoplasm from the cell responsible for synthesizing the myelin. Lateral loops are found in the paranodal region adjacent to the nodes of Ranvier, while Schmidt-Lantermann clefts are analogous structures found within the compact myelin internode.

nodes.name: Schmidt-Lanterman incisure
nodes.description: Regions within compact myelin in which the cytoplasmic faces of the enveloping myelin sheath are not tightly juxtaposed, and include cytoplasm from the cell responsible for making the myelin. Schmidt-Lanterman incisures occur in the compact myelin internode, while lateral loops are analogous structures found in the paranodal region adjacent to the nodes of Ranvier.

nodes.name: organelle
nodes.description: Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, vesicles, ribosomes and the cytoskeleton, and prokaryotic structures such as anammoxosomes and pirellulosomes. Excludes the plasma membrane.

nodes.name: membrane-bounded organelle
nodes.description: Organized structure of distinctive morphology and function, bounded by a single or double lipid bilayer membrane. Includes the nucleus, mitochondria, plastids, vacuoles, and vesicles. Excludes the plasma membrane.

nodes.name: cilium
nodes.description: A specialized eukaryotic organelle that consists of a filiform extrusion of the cell surface and of some cytoplasmic parts. Each cilium is largely bounded by an extrusion of the cytoplasmic (plasma) membrane, and contains a regular longitudinal array of microtubules, anchored to a basal body.

nodes.name: motile cilium
nodes.description: A cilium which may have a variable arrangement of axonemal microtubules and also contains molecular motors. It may beat with a whip-like pattern that promotes cell motility or transport of fluids and other cells across a cell surface, such as on epithelial cells that line the lumenal ducts of various tissues; or they may display a distinct twirling motion that directs fluid flow asymmetrically across the cellular surface to affect asymmetric body plan organization. Motile cilia can be found in single as well as multiple copies per cell.

nodes.name: 9+0 motile cilium
nodes.description: A motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets but no central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+0 axoneme).

nodes.name: 9+2 motile cilium
nodes.description: A motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets plus two central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+2 axoneme).

nodes.name: sperm flagellum
nodes.description: A microtubule-based flagellum (or cilium) that is part of a sperm, a mature male germ cell that develops from a spermatid.

nodes.name: left anterior flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It originates at the left anterior basal body, extends laterally through the cytoplasm, crosses the right anterior axoneme, and exits as a membrane-bound flagellum on the anterior left side of the cell.

nodes.name: right anterior flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It originates at the right anterior basal body, extends laterally through the cytoplasm, crosses the left anterior axoneme, and exits as a membrane-bound flagellum on the anterior right side of the cell.

nodes.name: left posteriolateral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left posteriolateral basal body and extends cytoplasmically toward the cell posterior, marking the left anterior boundary of the lateral shield and the left lateral region of the funis before exiting at the left lateral region of the cell body.

nodes.name: right posteriolateral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right posteriolateral basal body and extends cytoplasmically toward the cell posterior, marking the right anterior boundary of the lateral shield and the right lateral region of the funis before exiting at the right lateral region of the cell body.

nodes.name: left ventral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left ventral basal body and exits the cell body proximally and dorsal to the ventral disc.

nodes.name: right ventral flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right ventral basal body and exits the cell body proximally and dorsal to the ventral disc.

nodes.name: left caudal flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the left caudal basal body, extending cytoplasmically and exiting at the posterior end of the cell body.

nodes.name: right caudal flagellum
nodes.description: A cilium (also called flagellum) found in Giardia species (trophozoite stage). It is nucleated by the right caudal basal body, extending cytoplasmically and exiting at the posterior end of the cell body.

nodes.name: transverse flagellum
nodes.description: A motile cilium found in dinoflagellates. It coils around the cell and provides the forward thrust for motility. It is often contained in a furrow called the cingulum, and emerges from a flagellar pore located in the cingulum.

nodes.name: longitudinal flagellum
nodes.description: A motile cilium found in dinoflagellates. It trails the cell and acts as a steering rudder. It is often partially contained in a furrow called the sulcus, and emerges from a flagellar pore located in the sulcus.

nodes.name: non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A cilium which may have a variable array of axonemal microtubules but does not contain molecular motors.

nodes.name: 9+0 non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A non-motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets but no central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+0 axoneme).

nodes.name: photoreceptor cell cilium
nodes.description: A specialised 9+0 non-motile cilium found in photoreceptor cells. A ciliary transition zone called 'photoreceptor connecting cilium' links the photoreceptor outer segment to the inner segment.

nodes.name: 9+2 non-motile cilium
nodes.description: A non-motile cilium where the axoneme has a ring of nine outer microtubule doublets plus two central microtubules (and is therefore called a 9+2 axoneme).

nodes.name: kinocilium
nodes.description: A nonmotile primary cilium that is found at the apical surface of auditory receptor cells. The kinocilium is surrounded by actin-based stereocilia.

nodes.name: vesicle
nodes.description: Any small, fluid-filled, spherical organelle enclosed by membrane.

nodes.name: intracellular vesicle
nodes.description: Any vesicle that is part of the intracellular region.

nodes.name: cytoplasmic vesicle
nodes.description: A vesicle found in the cytoplasm of a cell.

nodes.name: contractile vacuole
nodes.description: A specialized vacuole of eukaryotic cells, especially Protozoa, that fills with water from the cytoplasm and then discharges this externally by the opening of contractile vacuole pores. One of its functions is osmoregulatory.

nodes.name: endosome
nodes.description: A vacuole to which materials ingested by endocytosis are delivered.

nodes.name: early endosome
nodes.description: A membrane-bounded organelle that receives incoming material from primary endocytic vesicles that have been generated by clathrin-dependent and clathrin-independent endocytosis; vesicles fuse with the early endosome to deliver cargo for sorting into recycling or degradation pathways.

nodes.name: postsynaptic early endosome
nodes.description: An early endosome of the postsynapse. It acts as the major sorting station on the endocytic pathway, targeting neurotransmitter receptors for degregation or recycling.

nodes.name: late endosome
